text=BOOK XXVI. %0a%0aA CONTINUATION OF THE REMEDIES DERIVED FROM %0aPLANTS, CLASSIFIED ACCORDING TO PARTICULAR %0aDISEASES. %0a%0aCHAP. 1. (1.)—NEW FORMS OF DISF.ASE. %0a%0aThe face of man has recently been sensible of new forms of %0adisease, unknown 1 in ancient times, not only to Italy, but to %0aalmost the whole of Europe. Still, however, they have not as %0ayet extended to the whole of Italy, nor have they made any %0avery great inroads in Illyricum, Gaul, or Spain, or indeed %0aany other parts, to so great an extent as in Rome and its en¬ %0avirons. Though unattended with pain, and not dangerous to %0alife, these diseases are of so loathsome a nature, that any form %0aof death would be preferable to them. %0a%0aCHAP. 2.-THE NATURE OF LICHEN. %0a%0aThe most insupportable of all these diseases is the one which, %0aafter its Greek appellation, is known to us as “ lichen.” 1 In %0aconsequence, however, of its generally making its first appear¬ %0aance at the chin, the Latins, by way of joke, originally— so %0aprone are'maukind to make a jest of the misfortunes of others %0a—gave it the name of “ mentagra ;” 2 an appellation which has %0asince become established in general use. In many cases, how¬ %0aever, this disease spreads over the interior of the mouth, and %0atakes possession of the whole face, with the sole exception of %0athe eyes ; after which, it passes downwards to the neck, breast, %0aand hands, covering them with foul furfuraceous eruptions. %0a%0aCHAP. 3.-AT WHAT PERIOB LICHEN FIRST MADE ITS APPEARANCE %0a%0aIN ITALY. %0a%0aThis curse was unknown to the ancients, 3 and in the times of %0aour fathers even, having first entered Italy in the middle of %0a%0a1 Probably as Littre suggests, a peculiar form of elephantiasis, the %0aleprosy of the middle ages. %0a%0ai The “chin disease from “ mentum,” tbe “ chin.” It is difficult to %0adetect the joke which has here incurred the censure of our author. %0a%0a3 Meaning the people of Italy. %0a%0a%0aChap. 3.] WHEN LICHEN FIUST APPEAHED IN ITALY. 153 %0a%0a%0athe reign of the Emperor Tiberius 4 * Claudius Caesar; where %0ait was introduced from Asia, 4 * in which country it had lately %0amade* its appearance, by a member of the equestrian order at %0aRome, a native of Perusium, secretary to the quaestor. The %0adisease, however, did not attack either females or slaves, 6 7 %0anor yet the lower orders, or, indeed, the middle classes, but %0aonly the nobles, being communicated even by the momentary %0acontact requisite for the act of salutation. 1 Many of those %0awho persevered in undergoing a course of remedial treatment, %0athough cured of the disease, retained scars upon the body more %0ahideous even than the malady itself; it being treated with %0acauteries, as it was certain to break out afresh, unless means %0awere adopted for burning it out of the body by cauterizing to %0athe very bone. %0a%0aUpon this occasion several physicians repaired to Pome %0afrom Egypt, that fruitful parent of maladies of this nature, %0amen who devoted themselves solely to this branch of medical %0apractice; and very considerable were the profits they made. %0aAt all events, it is a well-known fact that Manilius Cornutus, %0aa personage of praetorian rank, and legatus of the province of %0aAquitania, expended no less a sum than two hundred thou¬ %0asand 8 sesterces upon his cure. %0a%0aIt is much more frequently, on the other hand, that we hear %0aof new forms of diseases attacking the lower orders; a singular %0afact, and one quite unequalled for the marvellous phaenomena %0awhich sometimes attend these outbreaks. Thus, for instance, %0awe find an epidemic suddenly making its appearance in a cer¬ %0atain country, and then confining itself, as though it had made %0aits election so to do, to certain parts of the body, certain ages, %0aand even certain pursuits in life. In the same way, too, while %0a%0a4 It is somewhat difficult to say whether Tiberius, the predecessor, or %0aClaudius, the successor of Caligula, is meant; most probably the latter, %0aas the former’s reign would have been in the times of “ our fathers.” %0a%0a4 * Asia Minor. %0a%0a6 “ Cum apparuisset.” He is probably wrong here, for leprosy was %0aknown in Asia from the very earliest times. %0a%0a6 This assertion as to the slaves and lower orders is somewhat doubtful, %0athough it is very possible that the diet and habits of the higher orders %0aumy have predisposed them more particularly for the attacks of the diseases. %0a%0a7 “Osculi,” “kissing;” a nauseous and silly practice, still adhered to, %0abetween bearded men even, in many parts of Europe. %0a%0a11 Upwards of £1500. %0a%0a%0a154 %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVI. %0a%0a%0aone class of diseases attacks the young, another confines itself %0ato adults ; while one malady extends itself only to the hightr %0aclasses, another is felt exclusively by the poor. %0a%0aCHAP. 4 .- CARBUNCLE. %0a%0aWe find it stated in the Annals, that it was in the censorship 1 %0aof L. Paulus and Q. Marcius that carbuncle 10 was first intro- %0aduced into Italy, a malady which till then had confined itself %0asolely to the province of Gallia Narbonensis. In the year %0ain which I am writing these lines, two persons of consular %0arank have died of this disease, Julius Rufus 11 and Q. Lecanius %0aBassus ; 12 the former in consequence of an incision unskilfully %0amade by his medical attendants, the latter through a wound %0aupon the thumb of the left hand by pricking a carbuncle with %0aa needle, a wound so small originally as to be hardly percep¬ %0atible. %0a%0aThis disease makes its appearance in the more hidden 13 parts %0aof the human, body, and mostly beneath the tongue. It ori¬ %0aginally has the form of a hard, red, pimple, with a blackish %0ahead mostly, though sometimes of a livid colour. It produces %0atension of the flesh, but unattended with swelling, pain, or %0aany itching sensation ; indeed, the only symptom that accom¬ %0apanies it is a confirmed drowsiness, which overpowers the pa- %0atient, and carries him off in the course of three days. Some¬ %0atimes, however, it is accompanied with shuddering, and small %0apustules about the sore ; and occasionally, though but rarely, %0awith fever. When these symptoms extend to the fauces and %0aoesophagus, death ensues with the greatest rapidity. %0a%0aCHAP. 5.-ELEPHANTIASIS. %0a%0aWe have already 14 stated that elephantiasis 15 was unknown %0a%0a3 a.u.c 590. %0a%0a10 “ Carbunculus.” A malignant pustule, accompanied with swelling and %0aending with gangrene, is still known by this name, but it does not mani¬ %0afest any particular preference for the mouth and tongue. Fee says that %0acarbuncle was recently (1833) endemic in Provence, the ancient’Gallia %0aNarbonensis, for which reason it had received the name of “ Charbon Pro¬ %0avencal.” %0a%0a11 Consul, A.u.c. 819. 12 Consul, a.u.c. 816. %0a%0a13 Judging from this symptom, Dalechamps says that it looks more like %0achancre than carbuncle. u In B. xx. c. 52. %0a%0a15 Supposed, as Pliny says, to have originally come from Upper Egypt. %0a%0a%0aChap. G.] %0a%0a%0aCOLIC. %0a%0a%0a1 of) %0a%0ain Italy before the time of Pompeius Magnus. This malady, %0atoo, like those already mentioned, mostly makes its first ap¬ %0apearance in the face. In its primary form it bears a consider¬ %0aable resemblance to a small lentil upon the nose; the skin %0agradually dries up all over the body, is marked with spots of %0avarious colours, and presents an unequal surface, being thick %0ain one place, thin in another, indurated every here and there, %0aand covered with a sort of rough scab. At a later period, the %0askin assumes a black hue, and compresses the flesh upon the %0abones, the fingers and toes becoming swollen. %0a%0aThis disease was originally peculiar to Egypt. "Whenever it %0aattacked the kings of that country, it was attended with pe¬ %0aculiarly fatal effects to the people, it being the practice to %0atemper their sitting-baths with human blood, for tbe treatment %0aof the disease. As for Italy, however, its career was very %0asoon cut short: the same was the case, too, with the disease %0aknown as “ gemursa” 16 to the ancients, a malady which made %0aits appearance between the toes, and the very name of which is %0anow buried in oblivion. %0a%0a%0achap. 6.—COLIC. %0a%0aIt is a remarkable fact that some diseases should disappear %0afrom among us, while others, again, should continue to prevail, %0acolic 17 for example. It was only in the reign of Tiberius %0aCaesar that this malady made its appearance in Italy, the %0aemperor himself being the first to be attacked by it; a cir¬ %0acumstance which produced considerable mystification through¬ %0aout the City, when it read the edict issued by that prince %0aexcusing his inattention to public business, on the ground of his %0abeing laid up with a disease, the very name of which was till %0athen unknown. To what cause are we to attribute these various %0adiseases, or how is it that we have thus incurred the anger of %0athe gods ? Was it deemed too little for man to be exposed to %0a%0aLucretius, B. vi. 1. 1111, et seq ., attributes it to the water of the Nile. It %0ais but rarely known in Europe. %0a%0a16 Fee thinks that this may have been a sort of abscess similar to those %0abetween the fingers which are known as fourches by the French, and by %0amedical men as “ Aposthema phalangum.” Gruner considers it to be a sort %0aof Elephantiasis, and Triller identifies it with the disease called Gumretha %0aby the Talmudists. %0a%0a11 “ Colurn.” Fee takes this to be Schirrus of the colon. %0a%0a%0am %0a%0a156 pliny’s natural history. [BoolXXYL %0a%0afixed and determinate classes of maladies, already more than %0athree hundred in number, that he must have new forms of %0adisease to alarm him as well ? And then, in addition to all %0athese, not less in number are the troubles and misfortunes which %0aman brings upon himself! %0a%0aThe remedies which I am here describing, are those which %0awere universally employed in ancient times, Nature herself, %0aso to say, making up the medicines: indeed, for a long time %0athese were the only medicines employed. %0a%0a(2.) Hippocrates, 18 it is well known, was the first to com¬ %0apile a code of medical precepts, a thing which he did with the %0agreatest perspicuity, as his treatises, we find, are replete with %0ainformation upon the various plants. No less is the informa- %0ation which, we gain from the works of Diodes 19 of Carystus, %0asecond only in reputation, as well as date, to Hippocrates. %0aThe same, too, with reference to the works of Praxagoras, %0aChrysippus, and, at a later period, Erasistratus 20 of Cos. %0aHerophilus 21 too, though himself the founder of a more refined %0asystem of medicine, was extremely profuse of his commenda¬ %0ations of the use of simples. At a later period, however, expe¬ %0arience, our most efficient instructor in all things, medicine in | %0aparticular, gradually began to be lost sight of in mere words %0aand verbiage: it being found, in fact, much more agreeable %0ato sit in schools, and to listen to the talk of a professor, than %0ato go a simpling in the deserts, and to be searching for this %0aplant or that at all the various seasons of the year. %0a%0aCHAP. 7. (3.)- THE NEW SYSTEM OF MEDICINE: ASCLEP1ADE3 %0a%0aTHE PHYSICIAN. %0a%0aStill, however, the ancient theories remained unshaken, %0abased as they were upon the still existing grounds of uni¬ %0aversally acknowledged experience ; until, in the time of Pom- %0apeius Magnus, Asclepiades, 22 a professor of rhetoric, who %0aconsidered himself not sufficiently repaid by that pursuit, and %0awhose readiness and sagacity rendered him better adapted for %0aany other than forensic practice, suddenly turned his attention %0ato the medical art. Having never practised medicine, and %0abeing totally unacquainted with the nature of remedies—a %0a%0a18 See B. xxix. c. i. 13 See end of B. xx. %0a%0a20 See B. xxix. c. 3. 21 See B. xxix. c. 5. %0a%0a22 See end of B. vii. %0a%0a%0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 8.] CHANGES EFFECTED DY ASCLEPIADES. 157 %0a%0aknowledge only to be acquired by personal examination and %0aactual experience—as a matter of course, he was obliged to %0arenounce all previously-established theories, and to trust rather %0ato his flowing periods and his well-studied discourses, for %0againing an influence upon the minds of his audience. %0a%0aReducing the whole art of medicine to an estimation solely %0aof primary causes, he made it nothing but a merely con¬ %0ajectural art, and established it as his creed, that there are five %0agreat principles of treatment for all diseases in common ; diet, %0ause or non-use of wine, frictions, exercise on foot, and ex¬ %0aercise 23 in a carriage or on horseback. As every one perceived %0athat each of these methods of treatment lay quite within his %0aown reach, all, of course, with the greatest readiness gave %0atheir assent, willing as they were to believe that to be true %0awhich was so easy of acquisition; and hence it was that he %0aattracted nearly all the world about him, as though he had %0abeen sent among mankind on a special mission from heaven. %0a%0aCHAP. 8. -THE CHANGES EFFECTED BY ASCLEPIADES IN THE %0a%0aPliACTICE OF MEDICINE. %0a%0aIn addition to this, he had a wonderful tact in gaining the %0afull confidence of his patients : sometimes he would make them %0aa promise of wine, and then seize the opportune moment for %0aadministering it, while on other occasions, again, he would %0aprescribe cold water: indeed, as Herophilus, among the an¬ %0acients, had been the first to enquire into the primary causes of %0adisease, and Cleophantus had brought into notice the treat¬ %0ament of diseases by wine, so did Asclepiades, as we learn from %0aM. V arro, prefer to be indebted for his surname and repute %0ato the extensive use made by him of cold water as a %0aremedy, lie employed also various other soothing remedies %0afor his patients; thus, for instance, it was he that introduced %0aswinging beds, the motion of which might either lull the %0amalady, or induce sleep, as deemed desirable. It was he, %0atoo, that brought baths into such general use,—a method of %0atreatment that was adopted -with the greatest avidity—in %0auddition to numerous other modes of treatment of a pleasant %0aand soothing nature. By these means he acquired a great %0aprofessional reputation, and a no less extended fame; which %0a%0a23 “ Gestationesexercise on horseback, in a litter, or in a carriage %0adrawn by horses. %0a%0a%0a158 %0a%0a%0aplint’s natural iustory. %0a%0a%0a[Book XJYI. %0a%0a%0awas very considerably enhanced by the following incident: %0ameeting the funeral procession of a person unknown to him, %0ahe ordered the body to be removed from the funeral pile 24 and %0acarried home, and was thus the means of saving his life. This %0acircumstance I am the more desirous to mention, that it may %0anot be imagined that it was on slight grounds only that so %0aextensive a revolution was effected in the medical art. %0a%0aThere is, however, one thing, and one thing only, at which %0awe have any ground for indignation,—the fact, that a single %0aindividual, and he belonging to the most frivolous nation 24 in %0athe world, a man born in utter indigence, should all on a %0asudden, and that, too, for the sole purpose of increasing his %0aincome, give a new code of medical laws to mankind; laws, %0ahowever, be it remembered, which have been annulled by %0anumerous authorities since his day. The success of Asclepi- %0aades was considerably promoted by many of the usages of ancient %0amedicine, repulsive in their nature, and attended with far too %0amuch anxiety : thus, for instance, it was the practice to cover %0aup the patient with vast numbers of clothes, and to adopt %0aevery possible method of promoting the perspiration ; to order %0athe body to be roasted before a fire; or else to be continually %0asending the patient on a search for sunshine, a thing hardly to %0abe found in a showery climate like that of this city of ours; %0aor rather, so to say, of the whole of Italy, so prolific 25 * as it is %0aof fogs and rain. 26 It was to remedy these inconveniences, %0athat he introduced the use of hanging baths, 27 an invention %0athat was found grateful to invalids in the very highest %0adegree. %0a%0aIn addition to this, he modified the tortures which had %0ahitherto attended the treatment of certain maladies; as in %0aquinzv for instance, the cure of which before his time had been %0ausually effected by the introduction of an instrument 28 into the %0athroat. He condemned, and with good reason, the indiscrimi¬ %0anate use of emetics, which till then had been resorted to in a %0a%0a21 See B. vii. c. 37. Apuleius gives the story at considerable length, in %0athe Florida, B. iv. %0a%0a25 Asia Minor. Asclepiades was a native of Prusa in Bithynia. %0a%0aas* yve adopt Sillig’s suggestion, and read “ nimborum altrice,” the %0aword “ imperatrice ” being evidently out of place. The climate of Italy %0aseems to have changed very materially since bis day. %0a%0a26 See B. ii. c. 51. 27 See B. ix. c. 79. 26 “ Organo." %0a%0a%0aChap. 9.] REMARKS ON THE PRACTICES OF MAGIC. 159 %0a%0amost extraordinary degree. He disapproved also of the prac¬ %0atice of administering internally potions that are naturally %0ainjurious to the stomach, a thing that may truthfully be pro¬ %0anounced of the greater part of them. Indeed it will be as well %0ato take an early opportunity of stating what are the medi¬ %0acaments which, act beneficially upon the stomach. %0a%0aCHAP. 9. (4).- REMARKS IN DISPRAISE OF THE PRACTICES OF MAGIC. %0a%0aBut above all things, it was the follies of magic more par¬ %0aticularly that contributed so essentially to his success—follies %0awhich had been carried to such a pitch as to destroy all confi¬ %0adence in the remedial virtues of plants. Thus, for instance, %0ait was stoutly maintained that by the agency of the plant aethi- %0aopis 29 rivers and standing waters could be dried up, and that by %0athe very touch 30 * * * * all bars and doors might be opened : %0athat if the plant achaemenis 31 were thrown into the ranks of the %0aenemy it would be certain to create a panic and put them to %0aflight: that latace 32 was given by the Persian kings to their %0aambassadors, to ensure them an abundant supply of every¬ %0athing wherever they might happen to be: with numerous %0aother reveries of a similar nature. Where, I should like to %0aknow, were all these plants, when the Cimbri and Teutones %0abrought upon us the horrors of warfare with their terrific yells ? %0aor when Lucullus defeated, with a few legions, so many kings %0awho ruled over the Magi ? 33 Why is it too that the Roman %0agenerals have always made it their first care in warfare to %0amake provision for the victualling of their troops ? And how %0awas it that at Pharsalia the troops of Caesar were suffering from %0afamine, if an abundance of everything could have been ensured %0aby the fortunate possession of a single plant ? Would it not have %0abeen better too for Scipio JEmilianus to have opened the gates %0aof Carthage by touching them with a herb, than to have taken %0aso many years to batter down its bulwarks with his engines of %0awar? %0a%0aTurning to the present moment, let them, by the agency of %0athe herb menu's, 3 * dry up the Pomp tine 35 Marshes, if they can, %0a%0a29 See B. xxiv. c. 102. %0a%0aJ,J We agree with Pintianus that the name of some plant here has been %0alost, the word ‘‘condiendis ” making no sense. %0a%0a31 See B. xxiv. c. 102. %0a%0a32 Some plant as fictitious as the others here mentioned. %0a%0a33 See B. xxx. c. i. 31 See B. xxiv. c. 102. 33 See B. iii. c. 9. %0a%0a%0apunt’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a1 %0a%0a%0a160 %0a%0a%0a[nook 1XYI %0a%0a%0aand by these means restore so much territory to the regions of %0aItaly in the neighbourhood of our city. In the works, too, of %0aDemocritus, already mentioned, 36 we find a recipe for the compo¬ %0asition of a medicament which will ensure the procreation of %0aissue, both sure to be good and fortunate.—W hat king of Persia, %0apray, ever obtained that blessing ? It really would be a mar¬ %0avellous fact that human credulity, taking its rise originally in %0athe very soundest of notions, should have ultimately arrived at %0asuch a pitch as this, if the mind of man understood, under any %0acircumstances, how to keep within the bounds of modera¬ %0ation ; and if the very system of medicine thus introduced by %0aAsclepiades, had not been carried to a greater pitch of extra¬ %0avagance than the follies of magic even, an assertion which %0aI shall prove on a more appropriate occasion. 31 %0a%0aSuch, however, is the natural constitution of the human %0amind, that, be the circumstances what they may, commencing %0awith what is necessary it speedily arrives at the point of %0alaunching out in excess. %0a%0aWe will now resume our account of the medicinal properties %0aof the plants mentioned in the preceding Book, adding to our %0adescription such others as the necessities of the case may seem %0ato require. %0a%0a%0achap. 10.—lichen: five remedies. %0a%0aAs to the treatment of lichen, so noisome a disease as it is, %0awe shall here give a number of additional remedies for it, %0agathered from all quarters, although those already described %0aare by no means few in number. For the cure of lichea %0aplantago is used, pounded, cinquefoil also, root of albucus 1 ® in %0acombination with vinegar, the young shoots of the fig-tree %0aboiled in vinegar, or roots of marsh-mallow boiled down to %0aone-fourth with glue and vinegar. The sores are rubbed also %0awith pumice, and then fomented with root of rumex 39 bruised %0ain vinegar, or with scum of viscus 40 kneaded up with lime. A %0adecoction, too, of tithymalos 41 with resin is highly esteemed for %0athe same purpose. %0a%0aBut to all these remedies the plant known as “ lichen,” fro® %0a%0a36 In B. xxiv. c. 102. 37 In B. xxix. c. 5. %0a%0a33 See B. xxi. c. 68. 39 See B. xx. c. 85. %0a%0a40 “ Flos visci.” 41 See c. 39 of this Book. %0a%0a%0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 12.] %0a%0a%0aSCROFULA. %0a%0a%0a161 %0a%0a%0aits efficacy as a cure, is held in preference. It is found grow¬ %0aing among rocks, and has a single broad leaf 42 near the root, %0aand a single long stem, with small leaves hanging from it. %0aThis plant has the property also of effacing brand marks, %0abeing beaten up with honey for that purpose. There is another %0akind 43 of lichen also, which adheres entirely to rocks, like %0amoss, and which is equally used as a topical application. The %0ajuice of it, dropt into wounds, or applied to abscesses, has the %0aproperty of arresting haemorrhage: mixed with honey, it is %0acurative of jaundice, the face and tongue being rubbed with %0ait. Under this mode of treatment, the patient is recommended %0ato wash in salt water, to anoint himself with oil of almonds, %0aand to abstain from garden vegetables. For the cure of %0alichen, root of thapsia 44 is also used, bruised in honey. %0a%0aCHAP. 11.-QUINZY. %0a%0aFor the treatment of quinzy, we find argemonia 48 recom¬ %0amended, in wine; a decoction of hyssop, boiled with figs, %0aused as a gargle ; peucedanum , 46 with an equal proportion of %0asea-calf’s rennet; proserpinaca , 47 beaten up in the pickle of the %0amama 48 and oil, or else placed beneath the tongue; as also %0ajuice of cinquefoil, taken in doses of three cyathi. Used as a %0agargle, juice of cinquefoil is good for the cure of all affections %0aof the fauces : verbascum , 49 too, taken in wine, is particularly %0auseful for diseases of the tonsillary glands. %0a%0aCHAP. 12. (5.)—SCROFULA. %0a%0aFor the cure of scrofula 50 plantago is employed, chelidonia 61 %0amixed with honey and axle-grease, cinquefoil, and root of per- %0a%0a42 Identified by Fee with the Marchantia polymorphaof Linnseus, Com¬ %0amon Marchantia, or Fountain liverwort, the male plant. %0a%0a43 Identified by Fee with the Marchantia stellata, Star-headed Mar¬ %0achantia, or Female fountain liverwort. Dest'ontaines takes it to be either %0athe Marchantia conica, or the Peltidea canina. It must be remembered %0athat the Marchantia is not a Lichen in the modem acceptation of the word, %0aand that our Lichens are destitute of stem. Littre identifies it with the %0aLecanora parella. %0a%0a44 See B. xiii. c. 43. 45 See B. xxv. c. 56. %0a%0a46 See B. xxv. c. 70. 47 See B. xxvii. c. 104. %0a%0a44 See B. ix. c. 42. 49 See B. xxv. c. 73. %0a%0aw Fee remarks that none of the plants here mentioned are of any utility %0afor the cure of scrofula. 51 See B. xxv. c. 50. %0a%0aVOL. V. M %0a%0a%0a162 %0a%0a%0aPLINY'S natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVI. %0a%0a%0asolata 52 —this last being applied topically, and covered with the %0aleaf of the plant—artemisia , 63 also, and an infusion of the %0aroot of mandragora 64 in water. The large-leaved sideritis," %0acleft by the left hand with a nail, is worn attached as an %0aamulet: but after the cure has been effected, due care must be %0ataken to preserve the plant, in order that it may not be set %0aagain, to promote the wicked designs of the herbalists and so %0acause the disease to break out afresh ; as sometimes happens in %0athe cases already mentioned , 66 and others which I find stated, %0ain reference to persons cured by the agency of artemisia or %0aplantago. %0a%0aDamasonion , 57 also known as alcea, is gathered at the summer %0asolstice, and applied with rain-water, the leaves being beaten %0aup, or the root pounded, with axle-grease, so as to admit, when %0aapplied, of being covered with a leaf of the plant. The same %0aplan is adopted also for the cure of all pains in the neck, and %0atumours on all parts of the body. %0a%0aCHAP. 13. -THE PLANT CALLED BELLIS : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%