 is given, pounded, in astringent %0ared wine, for cough, asthma, and gripings in the bowels. It %0ais administered also in the form of a pottage, to which some %0awine should be added. For these complaints, gentian is also %0aused, being steeped in water the day before, and then pounded %0aand given in doses of one denarius, in three cyathi of wine. %0a%0aCHAP. 21.-GEUM : THREE REMEDIES. %0a%0aGeum 97 is a plant with thin, diminutive roots, black, and %0aaromatic. 90 It is curative not only of pains in the chest and %0asides, but is useful also for dispelling crudities, owing to its %0aagreeable flavour. Vervain, too, is good for all affections of %0athe viscera, and for diseases of the sides, lungs, liver, and %0a%0a91 See B. xxv. c. 20. 92 See B. xxv. c. 92. %0a%0a83 See B. xxv. c. 99. 91 See B. xxv. c. 100. %0a%0a95 See B. xxv. c. 64. %0a%0a96 Probably tbe Equisetum silvaticum of Linnaeus, our Wild horse-tail. %0aHe is in error in saying that it climbs the trunks of trees ; a mistake also %0amade by Dioscorides, B. iv. c. 46, who calls it “hippuris.” It is said by %0asome to be a strong diuretic. Littre, however, gives as its synonym the %0aEphedra fragilis of Linnaeus. %0a%0a97 The Geum urbanum of Linnaeus, tbe Common avens, or herb bennet. %0aIt was probably unknown to the Greeks. %0a%0a98 Its root has a smell like that of cloves, for which reason it is some¬ %0atimes known as “ Caryophyllata.’' %0a%0a%0aChap. 24.] %0a%0a%0aTHE MALUNDRUM. %0a%0a%0a167 %0a%0a%0athorax. But one invaluable remedy for diseases of the lungs, %0aand for cases of incipient phthisis, is the root of eonsiligo, a %0aplant only very recently discovered, as already" mentioned. It %0ais a most efficient remedy also for pulmonary diseases in swine %0aand cattle, even though only passed through the ear of the %0aanimal. When used, it should be taken in water, and kept %0afor a considerable time in the mouth, beneath the tongue. %0aWhether the part of this plant which grows above ground is %0