rt, Ceteracb, or %0aMiltwaste, or the A. hemionitis of Linnaeus, Mule’s fern. See B. xxvii. c. 17. %0a%0a13 See B. xxv. c. 54. 11 See B. xxv. c. 33. %0a%0a‘5 See B. xxv. c. 70. %0a%0a%0aChap. 28.] REMEDIES FOR DI8EA8ES OF THE BELLY. 169 %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 26.-HALUS OR COTONEA : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe plant halus, 16 by the people of Gaul called “sil,” and %0aby the Yeneti “ cotonea,” is curative of pains in the side, %0aaffections of the kidneys, ruptures, and convulsions. It resem¬ %0ables cunila bubula 17 in appearance, and the tops of it are like %0athose of thyme. It is of a sweet flavour, and allays thirst; the %0aroots of it are sometimes white, sometimes black. %0a%0aCRAP. 27.-THE CHAMAJROPS : ONE REMEDY. THE STCECHAS : %0a%0aONE REMEDY. %0a%0aThe chamaerops, 18 also, is similarly efficacious for pains in %0athe side. It is a plant with leaves like those of myrtle, %0aarranged in pairs around the stem, the heads of it resembling %0athose of the Greek rose : it is taken in wine. Agaric, admin¬ %0aistered in drink, in the same manner 19 as for cough, assuages %0asciatica and pains in the vertebrae : the same, too, with pow¬ %0adered stoechas 20 or betony, taken in hydromel. %0a%0aCHAP. 28. (8.)-REMEDIES FOR DISEASES OF THE BELLY. %0a%0aBut it is the belly, for the gratification of which the greater %0apart of mankind exist, that causes the most suffering to man. %0aThus, for instance, at one time it will not allow the aliments %0ato pass, while at another it is unable to retain them. Some¬ %0atimes, again, it either cannot receive the food, or, if it can, %0acannot digest it; indeed, such are the excesses practised at %0athe present day, that it is through his aliment, more than any¬ %0athing else, that man hastens his end. This receptacle, 21 more %0atroublesome to us than any other part of the body, is ever craving, %0alike some importunate creditor, and makes its calls repeatedly %0ain the day. It is for its sake, more particularly, that avarice %0ais so insatiate, for its sake that luxury is so refined, 22 for its sake %0athat men voyage to the shores even of the Phasis, for its sake %0athat the very depths of the ocean are ransacked. And yet, %0awith all this, no one ever gives a thought how abject is the %0acondition of this part of our body, how disgusting the results %0aot its action upon what it has received ! No wonder then, %0a%0a18 For the identity of this plant, see B. xxvii. c. 24. %0a%0a17 See B. xix. c. 50, and B. xx. c. 61. %0a%0a19 See B. xxiv. c. 80. 19 See c. 18 of this Book. %0a%0a3 " Identified with the Lavendula stoechas of Linnaeus, the French lavender. %0a%0a21 “ ' as.” 22 In search of pheasants. See B. vi. c. 4, %0a%0a%0apliny's natural history. %0a%0a%0a170 %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVI. %0a%0a%0athat the belly should have to be indebted to the aid of medicine %0ain the very highest degree ! %0a%0aScordotis, 23 fresh-gathered and beaten up, in doses of one %0adrachma, with wine, arrests flux of the bowels; an effect %0aequally produced by a decoction of it taken in drink. Pole- %0amonia, 24 too, is given in wine for dysentery, or two fingers’ %0alength of root of verbascum, 25 in water; seed of nymphaea %0aheraclia, 26 in wine ; the upper root of xiphion, 27 in doses of one %0adrachma, in vinegar; seed of plantago, beaten up in wine; %0aplantago itself boiled in vinegar, or else a pottago of alicu 2 * %0amixed with the juice of the plant; plantago boiled with %0alentils ; plantago dried and powdered, and sprinkled in drink, %0awith parched poppies pounded; juice of plantago, used as an %0ainjection, or taken in drink ; or betony taken in wine heated %0awith a red-hot iron. For coeliac affections, betony is taken in %0aastringent wine, or iberis is applied topically, as already 29 %0astated. For tenesmus, root of nymphaea heraclia is taken in %0awine, or else psyllion 30 in water, or a decoction of root of %0aacoron. 31 Juice of aizoiim 32 arrests diarrhoea and dysentery, and %0aexpels round tape-worm. Root of Symphytum, 33 taken in wine, %0aarrests diarrhoea and dysentery, and daucus 34 has a similar %0aeffect. Leaves of aizoum 33 beaten up in wine, and dried %0aalcea 36 powdered and taken in wine, are curative of griping %0apains in the bowels. %0a%0a%0achap. 29. —the astragalus: six remedies. %0a%0a%0aAstragalus 37 is the name of a plant which has long leaves, %0awith numerous incisions, and running aslant near the root. %0aThe stems are three or four in number, and covered with leaves: %0athe flower is like that of the hyacinth, and the roots are red, %0ahairy, matted, and remarkably hard. It grows on stony local- %0a%0a%0a23 See B. xxv. c. 27. %0a%0a25 See B. xxv. c. 73. %0a%0a21 See B. xxv. c. 89. %0a%0a29 In B. xxv. c. 84. %0a%0a31 See B. xxv. c. 100. %0a33 See B. xxvii. c. 24. %0a35 See Note 32 above. %0a%0a%0a24 See B. xxv. c. 28. %0a26 See B. xxv. c. 37. %0a28 See B. xviii. c. 29. %0a30 See B. xxv. c. 90. %0a32 See B. xxv. c. 102. %0a34 See B. xxv. c. 84. %0aSee B. xxvii. c. 6. %0a%0a%0a31 Sprengel identifies it with the Phaca Baetica, Spanish bastard vetch; %0ahut the flowers of that plant, as Fee remarks, are yellow. He consider? %0ait to he the Lathyrus tuberosus of Linnaeus, the Pease earth-nut. Littre %0agives the Orobus sessilifolius of Sibthorp. %0a%0a%0aChap. 30.] %0a%0a%0aLADANUM. %0a%0a%0ain %0a%0a%0aities, equally exposed to the sun and to falls of snow, those in %0athe vicinity of l’heneus in Arcadia, for instance. Its proper¬ %0aties are highly astringent; the root of it, taken in wine, arrests %0alooseness of the bowels, having the additional effect of throw¬ %0aing downward the aqueous humours, and so acting as a diuretic; %0aa property, in fact, which belongs>to most substances which %0aact astringently upon the bowels. %0a%0aBruised in red 37 * wine, this plant is curative of dysentery ; %0ait is only bruised, however, with the greatest difficulty. It is %0aextremely useful, also, as a fomentation for gum-boils. The %0aend of autumn is the time for gathering it, after the leaves ai’e %0aoff; it being then left to dry in the shade. %0a%0aCIIAP. 30.- LADANUM : EIGHTEEN REMEDIES. %0a%0aDiarrhoea may be also arrested by the use of either kind of %0aladanum. 38 The kind which is found in corn-fields is pounded %0afor this purpose, and then passed through a sieve, being taken %0aeither in hydromel, or in wine of the highest quality. “Ledon” %0ais the name of the plant from which ladanum 39 is obtained in %0aCyprus, it being found adhering to the beard of the goats %0athere; the most esteemed, however, is that of Arabia. 40 At %0athe present day, it is prepared in Syria and Africa also, being %0aknown as “ toxicum,” from the circumstance that ingathering %0ait, they pass over the plant a bow, 41 with the string stretched, %0aand covered with wool, to which the dewlike flocks of lada¬ %0anum adhere. We have described it at further length, when %0atreating of the perfumes. 42 %0a%0aThis substance has a very powerful odour, and is hard in the %0aextreme; for, in fact, there is a considerable quantity of earth %0aadhering to it: it is most esteemed when in a pure state, %0aaromatic, soft, green, and resinous. It is of an emollient, %0adesiccative, and ripening nature, and acts as a narcotic : it pre¬ %0avents the hair from falling off, and preserves its dark colour. In %0acombination Aviih hydromel or oil of roses, it is used as an %0a%0a,7 * “ Rubrum,” and not “ nigrum,” which Avas also what we call “ red ” %0awine. %0a%0a38 F6e is unable to identify it. The Galeopsis ladanum of Linnaeus, %0athe Red dead-nettle, has been suggested, but on insufficient grounds, pro¬ %0abably. 39 See B. xii. c. 37. %0a%0a40 It is still brought from the islands of Greece, but no longer from %0aArabia. 41 T o'£bv. %0a%0a42 In B. xii. c. 37. %0a%0a%0a172 %0a%0a%0aprint's natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVI. %0a%0a%0ainjection for the ears; with the addition of salt, it is employed %0afor the cure of furfuraceous eruptions of the skin, and for run¬ %0aning ulcers. Taken with storax, it is good for chronic cough; %0ait is also extremely efficacious as a carminative. %0a%0aCHAP. 31. -CHONDRIS OR PS^UDODICTAMNON : ONE REMEDY. HYPO- %0a%0aCISTHIS OR OROBETHRON ; TWO VARIETIES : EIGHT REMEDIES. %0a%0aChondris, too, or pseudodictamnon, 43 acts astringently on the %0abowels. Hypocisthis, 44 by some known also as “ orobethron,” %0ais similar to an unripe pomegranate in appearance; it grows, %0aas already stated, 46 beneath the cisthus, whence its name. %0aDried in the shade, and taken in astringent, red wine, these %0aplants arrest diarrhoea—for there are two kinds of hypocisthis, %0ait must be remembered, the white and the red. It is the juice %0aof the plant that is used, being of an astringent, desiccative, %0anature : that of the red kind, however, is the best for fluxes %0aof the stomach. Taken in drink, in doses of three oboli, with %0aamylum, 46 it arrests spitting of blood ; and, employed either as %0aa potion or as an injection, it is useful for dysentery. Vervain, %0atoo, is good for similar complaints, either taken in water, or, %0awhen there are no symptoms of fever, in Aminean 47 wine, the %0aproportion being five spoonfuls to three cyathi of wine. %0a%0aCHAP. 32. -LAVER 0^ SION : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aLaver, 48 too, a plant which grows in streams, preserved and %0aboiled, is curative of griping pains in the bowels. %0a%0aCHAP. 33. -POTAMOGITON: EIGHT REMEDIES. THE 8TATICE : %0a%0aTHREE REMEDIES. %0a%0aPotamogiton, 49 too, taken in wine, is useful for dysentery %0aand cceliac affections : it is a plant similar to beet in the leaves, %0abut smaller and more hairy, and rising but little above the %0asurface of the water. It is the leaves that are used, being of %0aa refreshing, astringent nature, and particularly good for %0adiseases of the legs, and, with honey or vinegar, for corrosive %0aulcers. %0a%0a45 “ False-dittany,” or “ bastard dittany.” See B. xxv. c. 53. %0a%0a44 The Cytinus hypocisthis of Linnaeus. %0a%0a45 In B. xxiv. c. 28. 46 See B. xviii. c. 17, and B.xxii. c. 67. %0a%0a47 See B. xiv. c. 5. 49 The Sium of B. xxii. c. 41. %0a%0a49 Probably the Potamogeton natans of Linnaeus, Broad-leaved pond- %0aweed, or some kindred plant. Its name signifies “ the neighbour of rivers.” %0a%0a%0aChap. 34.] %0a%0a%0aTHE CERATIA. %0a%0a%0a173 %0a%0a%0aCastor has given a different description of this plant. Ac¬ %0acording to him, it has a smaller leaf, 50 like horse-hair, 61 with a %0along, smooth, stem, and grows in watery localities. With the %0aroot of it he used to treat scrofulous sores and indurations. %0aPotamogiton neutralizes the effects of the bite of the crocodile; %0ahence it is that those who go in pursuit of that animal, are in %0athe habit of carrying it about them. %0a%0aAchillea 62 also arrests looseness of the bowels ; an effect %0aequally produced by the statice, 63 a plant with seven heads, like %0athose of the rose, upon as many stems. %0a%0aCUAP. 34. - THE CERATIA : TWO REMEDIES. LEONTOPODION, XET7- %0a%0aCEORON, DORIPETRON, OR THORYBETHRON. LAGOPUS : THREE %0a%0aREMEDIES. %0a%0aThe ceratia 64 is a plant with a single 55 leaf, and a large %0aknotted root: taken with the food, it is curative of coeliac %0aaffections and dysentery. *■ %0a%0aLeontopodion, 66 a plant known also as “ leuceoron,” “ dori- %0apetron,” or “ thorybethron,” has a root which acts astringently %0aupon the bowels and carries off bile, being taken in doses of %0atwo denarii in hydromel. It grows in champaign localities %0awith a poor soil: the seed, taken in drink, produces night-mare, 57 %0ait is said, in the sleep. %0a%0aLagopus 68 arrests diarrhoea, taken in wine, or, if there are %0asymptoms of fever, in water. This plant is attached to the %0agroin, for tumours in that part of the body: it grows in corn¬ %0afields. Many persons recommend, in preference to anything else, %0a%0a50 C. Bauhin and Sprengcl identify the plant here described with the %0aPotamogeton pusillum of Linnaeus; but Fee considers it extremely doubtful. %0a%0a61 A species of Equisetum would seem to be meant; indeed, Littre gives %0athe Equisetum telmateia. 52 See B. xxv. c. 19. %0a%0aM Fee thinks that this may possibly be the Statice Armeria of Linnams, %0aSea thrift, or Sea gilly-flower. %0a%0aM Considered by Sprengel to be the Cyclaminos chamsecissos of B. xxv. %0ac. 69, which he identifies with the Convallaria bifolia of Linnaeus, the %0aLittle lily of the valley, or May lily. Fabius Columna and Brotero con¬ %0asider it to be the Dentaria trifolia, Three-leaved toothwort. %0a%0a55 This is incorrect, if it is the Lily of the valley. %0a%0aM “ Lion’s paw,” “white plant,” or “rock-spear.” Probably the %0aLeontice leontopetalum of Linnaeus, Lion’s paw, or Lion’s leaf. See B. %0axivii. c. 72. 47 “ Lymphatica somnia.” %0a%0a^ “Hare’s foot.” Possibly the Trifolium arvense of Linnaeus, Hare’s %0afoot trefoil. %0a%0a%0a174 %0a%0a%0aPLINY’S natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XIYL %0a%0a%0afor desperate cases of dysentery, a decoction of roots of cinque¬ %0afoil in milk, or else aristolochia, 69 in the proportion of one %0avictoriatus 60 to three cyathi of wine. In the case of the pre¬ %0aparations above-mentioned, which are recommended to be taken %0awarm, it will be the best plan to heat them with a red-hot %0airon. %0a%0aOn the other hand, again, the juice of the smaller centaury %0aacts as a purgative upon the bowels, and carries off bile, taken, %0ain doses of one drachma, in one hemina of water with a little %0asalt and vinegar. The greater centaury is curative of griping %0apains in the bowels. Betony, also, has a laxative effect, taken %0ain the proportion of four drachmae to nine cyathi of hydromel: %0athe same, too, with euphorbia 61 or agaric, taken, in doses of two %0adrachma), with a little salt, in water, or else in three oboli of %0ahonied wine. Cyclaminos, 63 also, is a purgative, either taken %0ain water or used as a suppository; the same, too, with chamje- %0acissos, 66 employed as a suppository. A handful of hyssop, %0aboiled down to one third with salt, or beaten up with oxymel %0aand salt, and applied to the abdomen, promotes pituitous %0aevacuations, and expels intestinal worms. Root also of peu- %0acedanum 64 carries off pituitous humours and bile. %0a%0aCHAP. 35. -EPITHYMON OR HIPPOPHEOS : EIGHT REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe two kinds of anagallis, taken in hydromel, are purgative; %0athe same, too, with epithymon, 68 which is the blossom of a %0asort 66 of thyme similar to savory; the only difference being that %0athe flower of this plant is nearer grass green, while that of the %0aother thyme is white. Some persons call it “ hippopheos.”* 7 %0aThis plant is by no means wholesome to the stomach, as %0ait is apt to cause vomiting, but at the same time it disperses %0a%0a59 See B. xxv. c. 54. %0a%0a60 SeelntroductiontoYol.III. Fee remarks that none of the assertions %0ain the present Chapter are confirmed by modern experience. %0a%0a61 See B. xxv. c. 38. 92 See B. xxv. c. 67. %0a%0a65 See B. xxiv. cc. 49, 84, and B. xxv. c. 69. %0a%0a61 See B. xxv. c. 70. %0a%0a65 Identical with the Orobanche of B. xviii. c. 44, the Cuscuta Europtea %0aof Linnaeus, Dodder, Hell-weed, or Devil’s guts; or eke the Cuscuta %0aminor, or epithymum of Linnaeus. See also B. xxii. cc. 78, 80. %0a%0a66 He is in error here. %0a%0a67 Hardouin suggests “hypopheos,” as “ springing up under the Pheos” %0aor Stoebe, mentioned in B. xxii. c. 13. %0a%0a%0aChap. 37.1 %0a%0a%0aPOLYPODION. %0a%0a%0a175 %0a%0a%0aflatulency and gripings of the bowels. It is taken abo, in the %0aform of an electuary, for affections of the chest, with honey, %0aor in some cases, with iris. 68 Taken in doses of from four to %0asix drachmae, with honey and a little salt and vinegar, it %0arelaxes the bowels. %0a%0aSome persons, again, give a different description of epithymon: %0aaccording to them, it is a plant without 69 a root, diminutive, %0aandbearing a flower resembling a small hood, and of a red colour. %0aThey tell us, too, that it is dried in the shade and taken in %0awater, in doses of half an acetabulum; and that it has a slightly %0alaxative effect upon the bowels, and carries off the pituitous %0ahumours and bile. Nymphaea 70 is taken for similar purposes, %0ain astringent wine. %0a%0aCHAP. 36. -rYCNOCOMON ; FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%0aPycnocomon, 71 too, is a purgative. It is a plant with leaves %0alike those of rocket, only thicker and more acrid ; the root is %0around, of a yellow colour, and with an earthy smell. The %0astem is quadrangular, of a moderate length, thin, and sur¬ %0amounted with a flower like that of ocimum. 72 It is found %0agrowing in rough stony soils. The root, taken in doses of two %0adenarii in hydromel, acts as a purgative upon the bowels, %0aand effectually carries off bile and pituitous humours. The %0aseed, taken in doses of one drachma in wine, is productive of %0adreams and restlessness. Capnos, 73 too, carries off bile by the %0aurine. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 37. —POLYPODION : THREE REMEDIES. %0a%0aPolypodion, 74 known to us by the name of “ filicula,” hears %0asome resemblance to fern. The root of it is used medicinally ; %0a%0a68 See B. xxi. c. 19. %0a%0a89 It has a root originally, but the root withers as soon as it has attached %0aitself to the stem of the plant to which it clings. %0a%0a10 Sec B. xxv. c. 37. Holland says, on the contrary, that it is a binding %0aplant. %0a%0a71 “ Thick hair.” It is generally identified with the Leonurus mar- %0arnbiastrum of Linnaeus. Columna makes it to be the Scabiosa succisa of %0aLinnaeus, the Devil’s bit scabious, and Brunsfeld the Angelica silvestris of %0aLinnaeus, Wild angelica. %0a%0a73 See B. xxi. c. 60. 73 See B. xxv. c. 98. %0a%0a74 “ Many-footed.” The Polypodium vulgare of Linnaeus, the Common %0apolypody. %0a%0a%0a%0a176 punt’s NATURAL HISTORY. [Book XXVI. %0a%0abeing fibrous, and of a grass green colour within, about the %0athickness of the little finger, and covered with cavernous %0asuckers like those on the arms of the polypus. 1 his plant is of %0aa sweetish 15 taste, and is found growing among rocks and under %0atrees. The root is steeped in water, and the juice extracted; %0asometimes, too, it is cut in small pieces and sprinkled upon %0acabbage, beet, mallows, or salt meat; or else it is boiled with %0apap, 76 as a gentle aperient for the bowels, in cases of fever even. %0aIt carries off bile also and the pituitous' humours, but nets %0ainjuriously upon the stomach. Dried and powdered and ap¬ %0aplied to the nostrils, it cauterizes polypus 17 of the nose. It has %0aneither seed 18 nor flower. %0a%0aCHAP. 38.- SCAMMONY ; EIGHT REMEDIES. %0a%0aScammony, 19 also, is productive of derangement of the %0astomach. It carries off bile, and acts strongly as a purgative %0aupon the bowels; unless, indeed, aloes are added, in the propor¬ %0ation of two drachmae of aloes to two oboli of scammony. The %0adrug thus called is the juice of a plant that is branchy from %0athe root, and has unctuous, white, triangular, leaves, with %0aa solid, moist root, of a nauseous flavour: it grows in nch %0awhite soils. About the period of the rising of the Dog- %0astar, an excavation is made about the root, to let the juice %0acollect: which done, it is dried in the sun and divided into %0atablets. The root itself, too, or the outer coat of it, is some¬ %0atimes dried. The scammony most esteemed is that of Colophon, %0aMysia, and Priene. In appearance it ought to be smooth and %0ashiny, and as much like bull glue as possible : it should present %0aa fungous surface also, covered with minute holes ; should melt %0awith the greatest rapidity, have a powerful smell, and be sticky %0alike gum. "When touched with the tongue, it should give out %0aa white milky liquid; it ought also to be extremely light, and %0ato turn white when melted. %0a%0a75 It is for this reason that it is called “ reglisse,” or “ liquorice,” in %0asome parts of France. It contains a proportion of saccharine matter, %0awhich acts as a purgative. “ Pulticula.” %0a%0a17 This fancy is solely based on the accidental resemblance of the name. %0a%0a78 He very incorrectly says this of all the ferns. See B. xxvii. cc. 17, %0a48, and 55. %0a%0a79 The produce of the Convolvulus scammonia of Linnaeus, the Scam¬ %0amony bind-weed. The scammony of Aleppo is held in the highest esteem, %0aand is very valuable. That of Smyrna also is largely imported. %0a%0a%0aChap. 39.] %0a%0a%0aTHE TITHYMALOS CHARACIAS. %0a%0a%0a1 77 %0a%0a%0aThis last feature is recognized in the spurious scammony %0aalso, a compound of meal of fitches and juice of marine tithy- %0amalos, 80 which is mostly imported from Judea, and is very apt %0ato choke those who use it. The difference may be easily %0adetected, however, by the taste, as tithymalos imparts a burn¬ %0aing sensation to the tongue. To be fully efficacious, scammony %0ashould be two 81 years old; befpre or after that age it is useless. %0aIt has been prescribed to be taken by itself also, in doses of %0afour oboli, with hydromel and salt: but the most advanfageous %0amode of using it is in combination with aloes, care being taken %0ato drink honied wine the moment it begins to operate. The %0aroot, too, is boiled down in vinegar to the consistency of honey, %0aand the decoction used as a liniment for leprosy. The head is %0aalso rubbed with this decoction, mixed with oil, for head-ache. %0a%0aCHAr. 39.—TnE tithymalos characias. %0a%0aThe tithymalos is called by our people the “ milk plant,” 83 %0aand by some persons the “goat lettuce.” 83 They say, that if %0acharacters are traced upon the body with the milky juice of %0athis plant, and powdered with ashes, when dry, the letters will %0abe perfectly visible; an expedient which has been adopted %0abefore now by intriguers, for the purpose of communicating %0awith their mistresses, in preference to a correspondence by %0aletter. There are numerous varieties of this plant. 81 The %0afirst kind has the additional name of “ characias,” 85 and is %0agenerally looked upon as the male plant. Its branches are %0aabout a finger in thickness, red and full of juice, five or six in %0anumber, and a cubit in length. The leaves near the root are %0aalmost exactly those of the olive, and the extremity of the %0astem is surmounted with a tuft like that of the bulrush : it is %0afound growing in rugged localities near the sea-shore. The %0aseed is gathered in autumn, together with the tufts, and after %0abeing dried in the sun, is beaten out and put by for keeping. %0a%0a80 See the following Chapters. %0a%0a61 This assertion is erroneous; it has all its properties in full vigour im¬ %0amediately after extraction, and retains them for an indefinite period. %0a%0a83 “llcrba lactaria.” %0a%0a83 Because goats are fond of it. See B. xx. c. 24. %0a%0aM Known to us by the general name of Euphorbia of Spurge. %0a%0aM The Euphorbia characias of Linnaeus, Red spurge. An oil is still %0aextracted from the seed of several species of Euphorbia, as a purgative; %0abut they are in general highly dangerous, taken internally %0a%0aVOL. V. N %0a%0a%0a178 %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVI. %0a%0a%0aAs to the juice, the moment the down begins to appov %0aupon the fruit, the branches are broken off and the juice of %0athem is received upon either meal of fitches or else tigs, and %0aleft to dry therewith. Five drops are as much as each fig %0aought to receive; and the story is, that if a dropsical patient %0aeats one of these figs he will have as many motions as the fig %0ahas received drops. While the juice is being collected, due %0acare must be taken not to let it touch the eyes. From the leaves, %0apounded, a juice is also extracted, but not of so useful a %0anature as the other kind: a decoction, too, is made from the %0abranches. %0a%0aThe seed also is used, being boiled with honey and made up %0ainto purgative 86 pills. These seeds 