han doubtful. %0a%0a95 An assertion, Fee says, not confirmed by modern observation. %0a%0a%0a180 %0a%0a%0aflint’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVI. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 43. -THE TITHTMALOS CYPARISSIAS : EIGHTEEN REMEDIES. %0a%0aIn the fifth place we have the tithymalos known as “ cypa¬ %0arissias,” 96 from the resemblance of its leaves to those of the %0acypress. It has a double or triple stem, and grows in cham¬ %0apaign localities. Its properties are exactly similar to those of %0athe helioscopios and characias. %0a%0aCHAP. 44. -THE TITHTMALOS PLATTPHYLLOS, CORYMBITES, OR %0a%0aAMYGDALITES ! THREE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe sixth kind is called “ platyphyllos ” 97 by some, and %0a“ corymbites ” or “ amygdalites ” by others, from its resem¬ %0ablance to the almond-tree. The leaves of this kind are the %0alargest of all: it has a fatal effect upon fish. An infusion of %0athe root or leaves, or the juice, taken in doses of four drachmae, %0ain honied wine, or hydromel, acts as a purgative. It is par¬ %0aticularly useful also for carrying off the aqueous humours. %0a%0aCI1AP. 45. -THE TITHTMALOS DENDROIDES, COBIOS, OR LEPTO- %0a%0aPHYLLOS : EIGHTEEN REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe seventh kind has the additional name of “dendroides,”*' %0aand is known by some persons as “ cobios,” and by others as %0a“ leptophyllos.” 99 It grows among rocks, and is by far the %0amost shrubby of all the varieties of the tithymalos. The %0astems of it are small and red, and the seed is remarkably abun¬ %0adant. Its properties are the same as those of the characias. 1 %0a%0aCHAP. 46. -THE APIOS 1SCHAS, OR RAPHANOS AGRIA : TWO %0a%0aREMEDIES. %0a%0aThe apios ischas or raphanos agria, 2 throws out two or %0athree rush-like branches of a red colour, creeping upon the %0aground, and bearing leaves like those of rue. The root %0aresembles that of an onion, only that it is larger, for which %0a%0a86 The Euphorbia cyparissias of Linnaeus, the Cypress spurge, or else the %0aEuphorbia Aleppica of Linnaeus. %0a%0a97 “