aThe root, too, of lappa boaria, 46 taken in wine, is productive %0aof similar effects. A decoction of cyclaminos 47 in water, is cura¬ %0ative of chilblains, and all other affections resulting from cold. %0aFor chilblains, cotyledon 40 is also employed with axle-grease, %0aleaves of batrachion, 49 and juice of epithymum. 50 Ladanum," %0amixed with castoreum, 51 and vervain applied with wine, ex¬ %0atract corns from the feet. %0a%0aCHAP. 67.-MALADIES WHICH ATTACK THE WHOLE OF THE BODY. %0a%0aHaving now finished the detail of the diseases which are %0aperceptible in individual parts of the body, we shall proceed %0ato speak of those which attack the whole of the body. The %0afollowing I find mentioned as general remedies : in preference %0ato anything else, an infusion of dodecatheos, 52 a plant already %0adescribed, should be taken in drink, and then the roots of the %0aseveral kinds 53 of panaces, in maladies of long standing more %0aparticularly : seed, too, of panaces should be used for intestinal %0acomplaints. For all painful affections of the body we find %0ajuice of scordium 34 recommended, as also that of betony : this %0alast, taken in a potion, is particularly excellent for removing %0aa wan and leaden hue of the skin, and for improving its gene¬ %0aral appearance. %0a%0a40 See c. 19 of this Book. 41 See B. xviii. c. 14. %0a%0a42 See B. xx. c. 2. 43 See c. 37 of this Book. %0a%0a44 See B. xii. c. 28. 45 Seo B. xxiv. c. 88. %0a%0a46 “ Ox lappa.” Possibly the same as the Philanthropos, or else the %0a%0aLappa canina, both mentioned in B. xxiv. c. 116. %0a%0a47 See B. xxv. c. 67 . 48 See B. xxv. c. 101. %0a%0a49 See B. xxv. c. 109. %0a%0a50 See B. xii. c. 37, and c. 35 of this Book. %0a%0a61 See B. viii. c. 47. 52 See B. xxv. c. 9. %0a%0a33 See B. xxv. c. 11, et seq. 54 See B. xxv. c. 27. %0a%0a%0aChap. 68.] T1IE GEBANIOW. 195 %0a%0aCHAP. 68.-THE GERANION, MYRRHIS, OR MYRTIS ; THREE VARIE¬ %0a%0aTIES OF IT : SIX REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe plant geranion has the additional names of “ myrrhis” 54 ' %0aand “myrtis.” It is similar to hemlock in appearance, but %0ahas a smaller leaf and a shorter stem, rounded, and of a plea¬ %0asant taste and odour. Such, at all events, is the description %0agiven of it by our herbalists; but the Greeks speak of it as %0abearing leaves a little whiter than those of the mallow, thin %0adowny stems, and branches at intervals some two palms in %0alength, with small heads at their extremities, in the midst %0aof the leaves, resembling the bill 55 of a crane. 56 There is also %0aanother 57 variety of this plant, with leaves like those of the %0aanemone, but with deeper incisions, and a root rounded like %0aan apple, sweet, and extremely useful and refreshing 53 for %0ainvalids when recovering their strength; this last would al¬ %0amost seem to be the true geranion. %0a%0aFor phthisis this plant is taken, in the proportion of one %0adrachma to three cyathi of wine, twice a day; as also for %0aflatulency. Eaten raw, it is productive of similar effects. The %0ajuice of the root is remedial for diseases of the ear ; and for %0aopisthotony the seed is taken in drink, in doses of four drachmae, %0awith pepper and myrrh. Juice of plantago, 59 taken in drink, %0ais curative of phthisis, and a decoction of it is equally good for %0athe purpose. Plantago taken as a food w T ith oil and salt, %0aimmediately after rising in the morning, is extremely refreshing; %0ait is prescribed, too, in cases of atrophy, on alternate days. %0aBetony is given with honey, in the form of an electuary, for %0aphthisis, in pieces the size of a bean ; agaric, too, is taken in %0adoses of two oboli in raisiu wine, or else daucus 60 with the %0agreater centaury in wine. For the cure of phagedsena, a %0a%0aw * Not in reality the same plant as the Geranion ; see B. xxiv. c. 97. %0aLittre, however, gives the Erodium moschatum of Linnaeus as the synonym %0aot this Geranion myrrhis. %0a%0a55 Hence its name, from the Greek ytpavog, a “ crane.” %0a%0a50 This kind of Geranion has been identified with the Geranium molle, %0aor Erodiura malacoides of Linnaeus, the Common dove’s-foot crane’s bill. %0a%0a55 Identified with the Geranium tuberosum of Linnaeus. %0a%0a48 F6e remarks that all his assertions as to the medicinal properties of %0athe Geranion are erroneous. %0a%0a59 See B. xxv. c. 39. %0a%0a%0a60 See B. xxv. c. 64. %0a%0a%0a106 plint’s NATURAL UISTOUT. [Book XXVI. %0a%0aname given in common to bulimia 61 and to a corrosive kind %0aof ulcer, tithymalos 62 is taken in combination with sesame. %0a%0aCHAP. 69. -THE ONOTHERAS OH ONEAK : THREE REMEDIES. %0a%0aAmong the various evils by which the whole of the body in %0acommon is afflicted, that of wakefulness is the most common. %0aAmong the remedies for it we find panaces 63 mentioned, %0aclymenus, 61 and aristolochia, 63 the odour of the plant being %0ainhaled and the head rubbed with it. Aizoiira, or houseleek, %0ais beneficial, wrapped in black cloth and placed beneath the %0apillow, without the patient being aware of it. The onotheras" %0atoo, or onear, taken in wine, has certain exhilarating pro¬ %0aperties ; it has leaves like those of the almond tree, a rose- %0acoloured fiower, numerous branches, and a long root, with a %0avinous smell when dried: an infusion of this root has a %0asoothing effect upon wild beasts even. %0a%0aFor fits of indigestion 67 attended with nausea, betony is %0ataken in drink: used similarly after the evening meal, it faci¬ %0alitates the digestion. Taken in the proportion of one drachma %0ato three cyathi of oxymel, it dispels crapulence. The same is %0athe case, too, with agaric, taken in warm water after eating. %0aBetony is curative of paralysis, it is said; the same, too, with %0aiberis, as already stated. 68 This last is good, too, for numbness %0aof the limbs ; the same being the case with argemonia, w a %0aplant which disperses those affections which might otherwise %0anecessitate the application of the knife. %0a