he paroxysms come on; juice of the root of plantago made %0awarm or subjected to pressure; or else the root itself beaten up %0ain water made warm with a hot iron. Some medical men pre¬ %0ascribe three roots of plantago, in three eyathi of water ; and %0ain a similar manner, four roots for quartan fevers. When %0abuglossos 79 is beginning to wither, if a person takes the pith out %0aof the stem, and says while so doing, that it is for the cure %0aof such and such a person suffering from fever, and then %0aattaches seven leaves to the patient, just before the paroxysms %0acome on, he will experience a cure, they say. %0a%0aFevers too, those which are attended with recurrent cold %0ashiverings more particularly, are cured by administering one %0adrachma of betony, or else agaric, in three eyathi of hydromel. %0aSome medical men recommend three leaves of cinquefoil for %0atertian, four for quartan, and an increased number for other %0afevers; while others again prescribe in all cases three oboli of %0acinquefoil, with pepper, in hydromel. %0a%0a^ ervain, administered in water, is curative of fever, in beasts %0a%0a' 3 See B. xxiii. c. 16. 73 See B. xxi. c. 16. %0a%0a'* See B. xxiv. c. 88. 75 See B. xxv. c. 87. %0a%0aSee B. xxv. c. 70. 77 Sqe e. 30 of this Book. %0a%0aI# See B. xxv. c. 39. 79 See B. xxv. c. 40. %0a%0a%0a198 %0a%0a%0aPLINT’8 NATURAL ntSTOUT. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVI. %0a%0a%0aof burden even; but care must be taken, in cases of tertian %0afever, to cut the plant at the third joint, and of quartan fever %0aat the fourth. The seed of either kind of hypericon 90 is taken %0aalso for quartan fevers and cold shiverings. Powdered betony %0amodifies these fits, and panacea 81 is of so warming a nature %0athat persons when about to travel amid the snow are recom- %0amended to drink an infusion of it, and to rub the body all over %0awith the plant. Aristolochia 81 * also arrests shivering produced %0aby cold. %0a%0aCHAP. 72. -REMEDIES FOR PHRENITIS, LETHARGY, AND %0a%0a%0aCARBUNCLES. %0a%0a%0aPhrenitis is cured by sleep induced by the agency of an %0ainfusion of peucedanum 82 in vinegar, poured upon the head, or %0aelse by the juice of either kind of anagallis. 82 * On the other %0ahand, when patients are suffering from lethargy, it is with the %0agreatest difficulty that they are aroused ; a result which may %0abe effected, they say, by touching the nostrils with juice of %0apeucedanum in vinegar. For the cure of insanity, betony is %0aadministered in drink. Panaces 83 brings carbuncles to a head, %0aand makes them break; and they are equally cured by %0apowdered betony applied in water, or else cabbage leaves %0amixed with frankincense in warm water, and taken in con¬ %0asiderable quantities. For a similar purpose, a red-hot coai is %0aextinguished in the patient’s presence, and the ashes are taken %0aup with the finger and applied to the sore. Praised plantago* 3 * %0ais also used for the cure of carbuncles. %0a%0aCHAP. 73. —REMEDIES FOR DROPSY. ACTE OR EBULUM. %0a%0a%0aCHAMiEACTE, %0a%0a%0aFor the cure of dropsy, tithymalos characias 84 is employed; %0apanaces 85 also; plantago, 66 used as a diet, dry bread being %0aeaten first, without any drink; betony, taken in doses of two %0adrachmae in two cyathi of ordinary wine or honied wine; %0aagaric or seed of lonchitis, 87 in doses of two spoonfuls, in %0a%0a90 See Chapters -53 and 54 of this Book. %0a%0a%0a81 See B. xxv. c. 11, et seq. %0a32 See B. xxv. e. 70. %0a%0a%0a*'* See B. xxv. c. 54. %0a82 * See B. xxv. c. 92. %0aw * See B. xxv. c. 39. %0a%0a%0a83 See B xxv. c. 11, et seq. %0a81 See c. 39 of this Book. %0a%0a86 See B. xxv. c. 39. %0a%0a%0a85 See B. xxv. c. 11, et seq. %0a87 See B. xxv. c. 88. %0a%0a%0aREMEDIES FOR ERYSIPELAS. %0a%0a%0a199 %0a%0a%0aChap. 74.] %0a%0awater; psyllion, 88 taken in wine; juice of either anagallis; 89 %0aroot of cotyledon 90 in honied wine; root of ebulum, 91 fresh %0agathered, with the mould shaken off, but not washed in %0awater, a pinch in two fingers being taken in one hemina of %0aold wine mulled; root of trefoil, taken in doses of two %0adrachmae in wine ; the tithymalos 92 known as “ platyphyllos;” %0aseed of the hypericon, 93 otherwise known as “ caros;” the %0aplant called “ acte”—the same thing as ebulum 91 according to %0asome—the root of it being pounded in three cyathi of wine, if %0athere are no symptoms of fever, or the seed of it being ad¬ %0aministered in red wine; a good handful of vervain also, boiled %0adown in water to one half. But of all the remedies for this %0adisease, juice of chamaeacte 95 is looked upon as bjr far the most %0aefficacious. %0a%0aMorbid or pituitous eruptions are cured by the agency of %0aplantago, or else root of cyclaminos 96 with honey. Leaves of %0aebulum, 97 bruised in old wine and applied topically, are curative %0aof the disease called “ boa,” which makes its appearance in %0athe form of red pimples. Juice of strychnos, 98 applied as a %0aliniment, is curative of prurigo. %0a%0a%0aCUAP. 74. -REMEDIES FOR ERYSIPELAS. %0a%0aFor the cure of erysipelas, aizoum" is used, or else pounded %0aleaves of hemlock, or root of mandragora ; 3 this last being cut %0ainto round slices like cucumber and suspended over must, 2 after %0awhich it is hung up in the smoke, and then pounded in wine %0aor vinegar. It is a good plan too to use fomentations with %0amyrtle w'ine : two ounces of mint beaten up in vinegar with %0aone ounce of live sulphur, form a mixture sometimes employed; %0aas also soot mixed with vinegar. %0a%0aThere are several kinds of erysipelas, one in particular %0awhich attacks the middle of the body, and is known as %0a“zoster:” 3 should it entirely surround the body, its effects are %0a%0a%0a•* See B. xxv. c. 90. %0a%0a90 See B. xxv. c. 101. %0a%0a92 See c. 44 of this Book. %0a%0aM See B. xxv. c. 71. %0a%0a96 See B. xxv. c. 67. %0a%0a98 See B. xxi. c. 105. %0a%0a1 See B. xxv. c. 94. %0a%0a3 The “ belt ”—known to us as %0a%0a%0a69 See B. xxv. c. 92. %0a%0a9