 %0aand honey. Boot of cyclaminos 11 is also taken in drink in %0adoses of three drachmae, the patient sitting in a warm room %0afree from all cold and draughts, the infusion expelling the %0abile by its action as a sudorific. %0a%0a%0a4 See B. xxv. c. 39. %0a%0a6 See B. xxv. c. 66. %0a%0a8 See B. xxv. c. 102. %0a%0a10 See c. 37 of this Book. %0a12 See B. xxv. c. 39. %0a%0a14 See B. xxv. c. 107. %0a%0a16 See B. xxv. c. 3'J. %0a%0a%0a5 See B. xxxv. c. 57. %0a%0aI See B. xxv. c. 101. %0a9 See B. xxv. c. 18. %0a%0aII See B. xxv. c. 90. %0a13 See B. xxv. c. 73. %0a13 B. iv. cc. 62, 64. %0a%0a17 See B. xxv. c. 67. %0a%0a%0a'hap. 79.] %0a%0a%0aREMEDIES FOE ABSCESSES. %0a%0a%0a201 %0a%0a%0aLeaves of tussilago 18 are also used in water for this purpose ; %0athe seed of either kind of linozostis, 19 sprinkled in the drink, or %0amade into a decoction with chick-pease or wormwood : hyssop %0aberries taken in water; the plant lichen,'- 0 all other vege¬ %0atables being carefully abstained from while it is being used; %0apolythrix, 21 taken in wine; and struthion, 22 in honied wine. %0a%0aCHAP. 77. -KEMEDIES FOE BOILS. %0a%0aThere are boils also, known as “ furunculi,” 23 which make %0atheir appearunce indiscriminately on all parts of the body, and %0aare productive of the greatest inconvenience: sometimes %0aindeed, when the constitution is exhausted, they are fatal in %0atheir effects. For their cure, leaves of pycnocomon 24 are em¬ %0aployed, beaten up with polenta, 25 if the boil has not come to a %0abead. They are dispersed also by an application of leaves of %0aephedron. 26 %0a%0aCHAP. 78. -EEMEDIES FOE FISTULA. %0a%0aFistulas, too, insidiously attack all parts of the body, owing %0ato unskilfulness on the part of medical men in the use of the %0aknife. The smaller centaury 27 is used for their cure, with the %0aaddition of lotions 28 and boiled honey : juice of plantago 29 is %0aalso employed, as an injection ; cinquefoil, mixed with salt and %0ahoney; ladauum, 30 combined with castoreum ; 31 cotyledon, 32 %0aapplied hot with stag’s marrow ; pith of the root of verbascum 33 %0areduced to a liquid state in the shape of a lotion, and injected ; %0aroot of aristolochia ; 34 or juice of tithymalos. 35 %0a%0a%0aCTlAr. %3c9.—REMEDIES FOR ABSCESSES AND HARD TUMOURS. %0a%0aAbscesses and inflammations are cured by an application of %0aleaves of argemonia. 36 For indurations and gatherings of all %0adescriptions a decoction of vervain or cinquefoil in vinegar is %0a%0a%0als Or Beckion. See B. xxiv. c. 85. %0a19 See B. xxv. c. 19. %0a%0a21 Sec B. xxv. c. 83. %0a%0aM “ Little thieves,” literally. %0aa See B. xviii. c. 14. %0a%0a" See B. xxv. c. 31. %0a%0a2S See B. xxv. c. 39 30 See %0a%0a31 See B. viii. c. 47. %0a%0a53 See B. xxv. c. 73. %0a%0a34 See c. 39 of this Book. %0a%0a%0a20 See c. 10 of this Book. %0a%0a22 See B. xix. c. 18. %0a%0a24 See c. 36 of this Book. %0a%0a26 See c. 83 of this Book. %0a%0a28 “Collyriis.” %0a%0aB. xii. c. 37, and c. 30 of this Book. %0a32 See B. xxv. c. 101. %0a%0a34 See B. xxv. c. 54. %0a%0a36 See B. xxv. c. 56. %0a%0a%0a%0a%0a202 %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVI. %0a%0a%0aused ; leaves or root of verbascum ; 37 a liniment made of wine %0aand hyssop ; root of acoron, 38 a decoction of it being used as a %0afomentation ; or else aizoiim. 39 Contusions also, hard tumours, %0aand fistulous abscesses are treated with illecebra. 40 %0a%0aAll kinds of foreign substances which have pierced the %0aflesh are extracted by using leaves of tussilago, 41 daucus, 43 or %0aseed of leontopodium 43 pounded in water with polenta. 44 To %0asuppurations, leaves of pycnocomon 45 are applied, beaten up %0awith polenta, or else the seed of that plant, or orchis. 46 An %0aapplication of root of satyrion 47 is said to be a most efficacious %0aremedy for deep-seated diseases of the bones. Corrosive ulcere %0aand all kinds of gatherings are treated with sea-weed, 48 used %0abefore it has dried. Root, too, of alcima 49