d or %0achewed. For spasmodic affections, fits of trembling, and opis¬ %0athotony, root of alcima 63 is administered in hydromel; used in %0athis manner, it has a warming effect when the limbs are %0abenumbed with cold. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 82. -REMEDIES FOR HAEMORRHAGE. %0a%0aThe red seed of the plant called “ paeonia” 64 arrests haemorr¬ %0ahage ; the root also is possessed of similar properties. But it %0ais clymenus 65 that should be employed, when there are dis¬ %0acharges of blood at the mouth or nostrils, from the bowels, or %0afrom the uterus. In such cases, lysimachia 66 also is taken in %0adrink, applied topically, or introduced into the nostrils ; or %0aelse 6eed of plantago, 67 or cinquefoil, is taken in drink, or em¬ %0aployed in the form of a liniment. Hemlock seed is introduced %0ainto the nostrils, for discharges of blood there, or else it is %0apounded and applied in water; aizoiim 6 * also, and root of as¬ %0atragalus. 69 Isehaemon 70 and achillea 71 likewise arrest haemorr¬ %0ahage. %0a%0aCHAP. 83. (13.) -HIPPURIS, OTHERWISE CALLED EPBEDRON, %0a%0aANABASIS, OR EQUISJ3TUM ; THREE KINDS OF IT : EIGHTEEN %0aREMEDIES. %0a%0a%0aEquisaetum, a plant called “ hippuris” by the Greeks, and %0awhich we have mentioned in terms of condemnation, when %0atreating of meadow lands 72 —it being, in fact, a sort of hair of %0athe earth, similar in appearance to horse-hair 75 —is used by %0arunners for the purpose of diminishing 74 the spleen. For this %0a%0a%0a61 See c. 53 of this Book. 62 See B. xxv. c. 76. %0a%0a63 See Note 49 above. 64 Our peony. See B. xxv. c. 10. %0a%0a65 See B. xxv. c. 33. 66 See B. xxv. c. 35. %0a%0a67 See B. xxv. c. 39. 68 See B. xxv. c. 102. %0a%0a69 See c. 29 of the present Book. 70 See B. xxv. c. 45. %0a%0a71 See B. xxv. c. 19. %0a%0a79 In B. xviii. c. 67 ; where it is called “ equiscetis.” M. Fraas identifies %0ait with the Equisaetum limosum of Linnaeus. %0a%0a73 Whence its name “ equisaetum.” %0a%0a71 See B. xi. c. 30. %0a%0a%0a204 %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVI. %0a%0a%0apurpose it is boiled down in a new earthen vessel to one third, %0athe vessel being filled to the brim, and the decoction taken %0ain doses of one hemina for three successive days. It is strictly %0aforbidden, however, to eat any food of a greasy nature the day %0abefore taking it. %0a%0aAmong the Greeks there are various opinions in relation to %0athis plant. According to some, who give it the same name of %0a“ hippuris,” it has leaves like those of the pine tree, and of a %0aswarthy hue; and, if we are to believe them, it is possessed of %0avirtues of such a marvellous nature, that if touched by the %0apatient only, it will arrest haemorrhage. Some authorities call it %0a“hippuris,’’others, again, “ ephedron,” and others “anabasis;” %0aand they tell us that it grows near trees, the trunks of which it %0aascends, and hangs down therefrom in numerous tufts of black, %0arush-like hair, much like a horse’s tail in appearance. The %0abranches, we are told, are thin and articulated, and the leaves, %0afew in number, small, and thin, the seed round, and similar to %0acoriander in appearance, and the root ligneous: it grows, they %0asay, in plantations more particularly. %0a%0aThis plant is possessed of astringent properties. The juice %0aof it, kept in the nostrils, arrests bleeding therefrom, and it %0aacts astringently upon the bowels. Taken in doses of three %0acyathi, in sweet wine, it is a cure for dysentery, is an efficient %0adiuretic, and is curative of cough, hardness of breathing, rup¬ %0atures, and serpiginous affections. For diseases of the intestines %0aand bladder, the leaves are taken in drink; it has the property, %0aalso, of reducing ruptures of the groin. %0a%0aThe Greek writers describe another 15 hippuris, also, with %0ashorter tufts, softer and whiter. This last, they say, is remark¬ %0aably good for sciatica, and, applied with vinegar, for wounds, %0ait having the property of stanching the blood. Bruised nyrn- %0apluea 16 is also applied to wounds. Peucedanum 17 is taken in drink %0awith cypress seed, for discharges of blood at the mouth or by %0athe lower passages. Sideritis 79 is possessed of such remark¬ %0aable virtues, that applied to the wound of a gladiator just %0ainflicted, it will stop the flow of blood; an effect which is equally %0aproduced by an application of charred fennel-giant, or of the %0a%0a75 Identified by Littre with the Ephedra fragilis of Linnaeus. Feegivs %0aas its synonym the Equisaetum arvense of Linnaeus, the Common horse-tail, %0aor Corn horse-tail. 76 See B. xxv. c. 37. %0a%0a77 See B. xxv. c. 70. 78 See B. xxv. c. 15. %0a%0a%0a(!hap. 85.] %0a%0a%0aREMEDIES EOR RUPTURES. %0a%0a%0a205 %0a%0a%0aashes of that plant. For a similar purpose, also, the fungus %0athat is found growing near the root of fennel-giant is still %0amore efficacious. %0a%0a%0aCHAr. 84. -STEPHANOMELIS. %0a%0aFor bleeding at the nostrils, seed of hemlock, pounded in %0awater, is considered efficacious, as also stephanomelis, 79 applied %0awith water. Powdered betony, taken with goat’s milk, or %0abruised plantago, 80 arrests discharges of blood from the ma- %0amillae. Juice of plantago is administered to patients when %0avomiting blood. For local discharges of blood, an application of %0aroot of persolata 81 with stale axle-grease is highly spoken of. %0a%0a%0aCUAP. 85.- REMEDIES POR RUPTURES AND CONVULSIONS. %0a%0aERYSITHALES : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aFor ruptures, convulsions, and falls with violence, the greater %0acentaury 83 is used; root of gentian pounded or boiled ; juice of %0abetony—this last being employed also for ruptures produced by %0astraining the vocal organs or sides—panaces ; 83 scordium ; 84 or %0aaristolochia 85 taken in drink. For contusions and falls, agaric %0ais taken, in doses of two oboli, in three cyathi of honied wine, %0aor if there are symptoms of fever, hydromel; the verbascum, 86 %0aalso, with a golden flower; root of acoron ; 87 the several varieties %0aof aizoiini, 88 the juice of the larger kind being particularly %0aefficacious; juice of Symphytum, 89 or a decoction of the root of %0athat plant; daucus, 90 unboiled; erysithales, 91 a plant with a %0ayellow flower and a leaf like that of acanthus, taken in wine; %0achamaerops ; 93 irio, 93 taken in pottage; plantago 94 taken any %0away, as also * * * * %0a%0a%0a78 Daleckamps identifies it with the Potcntilla anserina of Linnaeus, %0aSilver-weed, or White tansy; but on insufficient grounds, Fee thinks. %0a%0aM See B. xxv. c. 39. 81 See B. xxv. c. 66. %0a%0a83 See B. xxv. c. 30. 83 See B. xxv. c. 11, ct seq. %0a%0a84 See B. xxv. c. 27 . 85 See B. xxv. c. 54. %0a%0a" e See B. xxv. c. 73. 87 See B. xxv. c. 100. %0a%0a88 See B. xxv. c. 102. 89 See B. xxvii. c. 24. %0a%0a90 See B. xxv. c. 64. %0a%0a91 C. Bauhin identifies it with the Cnicus erysithales of Willdenow; %0abid that plant, Fee says, was unknown to the Greeks. %0a%0a93 See B. xxiv. c. 80. 93 See B. xviii. c. 10. %0a%0a91 See B. xxv. c. 39. %0a%0a%0a206 %0a%0a%0apliny's natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVI, %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 86.-REMEDIES FOR PHTHIRIASIS. %0a%0aPhthiriasis is a disease which proved fatal to the Dictator %0aSylla, 95 and which developes itself by the production of insects %0ain the blood, which ultimately consume the body. It is combated %0aby using the juice of Taminian grapes 95 or of hellebore, the %0abody being rubbed all over with it, in combination with oil. %0aA decoction of Taminian grapes in vinegar, has the effect, also, %0aof ridding the clothes of these vermin. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 87. (14.) -REMEDIES FOR ULCERS AND WOUNDS. %0a%0aOf ulcers there are numerous kinds, which are treated in %0avarious ways. The root of all the varieties of panaces 97 is %0aused as an application for running ulcers, in warm wine. %0a%0aThat which we have spoken of as the “ chironion” 98 is par¬ %0aticularly good as a desiccative: bruised with honey, it opens %0atumours, and is useful for serpiginoyus ulcers, the cure ofwhich %0aappears more than doubtful; in which case it is amalgamate! %0awith flower 99 of copper tempered with wine, either the seed, %0aflower, or root, being employed for the purpose. Mixed with %0apolenta 1 it is good for old wounds. The following are also %0agood detergents for wounds : heraclion siderion, 2 apollinaris/ %0apsyllion, 4 tragacantha, 6 and scordotis 6 mixed with honey. %0aPowdered scordotis, applied by itself, consumes fleshy excres¬ %0acences on the body. Polemonia 7 is curative of the malignant %0aulcer known as “ cacoethes.” The greater centaury, 8 sprinkled %0ain powder, or applied in the form of a liniment, or the leaves of %0athe smaller 9 centaury, boiled or pounded, act as a detergent %0aupon inveterate ulcers, and effect a cure. To recent wounds, %0athe follicules of the clymenus 10 are applied. Gentian is applied %0ato serpiginous ulcers, the root being bruised or else boiled down %0ain water to the consistency of honey ; the juice also of the %0aplant is employed. For wounds, a kind of lycium 11 is prepared %0afrom gentian. %0a%0a%0a95 See B. xi. c. 39, and B. xx. c. 32 . 96 See B. xxiii. c. 13. %0a%0a97 See B. xxv. c. 11, et seq. 98 See B. xxv. c. 15. %0a%0a99 For a description of this substance, see B. xxxiv. c. 24. %0a%0a1 See B. xviii. c. 14. 2 See B. xxv. c. 15. %0a%0a3 See B. xxv. c. 17. 4 See B. xxv. c. 90. %0a%0a8 See B. xiii. c. 36. 6 See B. xxv. c. 27. %0a%0a7 See B. xxv. c. 28. 8 See B. xxv. c. 30. %0a%0a9 See B. xxv. c. 31. 10 See B. xxv. c. 33. %0a%0a%0a11 See B. xxiv. c. 77. %0a%0a%0aREMEDIES FOR ULCERS. %0a%0a%0a207 %0a%0a%0aChap. 87.] %0a%0aLysiraachia 12 is curative of recent wounds, and plantago 13 of %0aall kinds of ulcerations,those on females, infants, and aged per¬ %0asons more particularly. This plant, when softened by the action %0aof fire, is better still: in combination with cerate it acts as a %0adetergent upon ulcers with indurated edges, and arrests the %0aprogress of corrosive sores: when applied bruised, it should be %0acovered with its own leaves. Chelidonia 14 also acts as a %0adesiccative upon suppurations, abscesses, and fistulous ulcers ; %0aindeed, it is so remarkably useful for the cure of wounds, as %0ato be employed as a substitute for spodium 15 even. In cases %0awhere the cure is almost hopeless, it is applied with axle- %0agrease. Dittany, 16 taken internally, causes arrows to fall from %0athe flesh ; used as a liniment, it has the effect of extracting other %0akinds of pointed weapons: the leaves are taken in the pro¬ %0aportion of one obolus to one cyathus of water. Nearly equal %0ain its efficacy is pseudo-dictamnon : 17 they are both of them %0auseful, also, for dispersing suppurations. %0a%0aAristolochia 18 cauterizes putrid sores, and, applied with honey, %0aacts as a detergent upon sordid ulcers. At the same time also, %0ait removes maggots, and extracts hard cores, and all foreign %0abodies adhering to the flesh, arrows more particularly, and, %0aapplied with resin, splintered bones. Used by itself, it fills the %0acavities made by ulcers with new flesh, and, employed with %0ahis, 19 in vinegar, it closes recent wounds. Vervain, or cinque¬ %0afoil with salt and honey, is remedial for ulcers of long stand¬ %0aing. Roots of persolata 20 are applied to recent wounds in¬ %0aflicted with iron, but for old wounds, it is the leaves that are %0aemployed : in both cases, in combination with axle-grease, the %0asore being then covered with the leaves of the plant. Damaso- %0aniunr 1 is used for wounds the same way as for scrofula, 22 and %0aleaves of verbascum 23 are employed with vinegar or wine. %0a%0aVervain is useful for all kinds of callosities or putrid sores; %0aroot of nymphaea heraclia 24 is curative of running ulcers ; and %0a%0a12 See B. xxv. c. 35. 13 See B. xxv. c. 39. %0a%0a14 See B. xxv. c. 50. %0a%0a15 See B. xix. c. 4, B. xxiii. c. 35, and B. xxxiv. c. 52. %0a%0a16 See B. xxv. c. 53. %0a%0a17 Bastard dittany. See