y and vinegar, they are %0acurative of the ulcer known as “ cacoethes.” Onothera 39 also, %0aused by itself, is curative of ulcers when rapidly gaining head. %0a%0aThe people of Scythia employ scythice 40 for the treatment %0aof wounds. For carcinoma, argemonia, 41 applied with honey, %0ais extremely efficacious. For sores that have prematurely %0aclosed, root of asphodel is boiled, in manner already 12 stated. %0a%0a%0a25 See B. xxv. c. 67. %0a%0a27 See B. xxv. c. 92. %0a%0a29 “ Siligo.” See B. xviii. c. 20. %0a%0a31 See B. xxv. c. 106. %0a%0a33 See c. 31 of this Book. %0a%0a34 See B. xxviii. c. 14. %0a%0a37 See c. 39 of this Book. %0a%0a39 See c. 69 of this Book. %0a%0a40 Our “ liquorice/’ see B. xxv. c. %0a%0a41 See B. xxv. c. 66. %0a%0a%0a28 See B. xxv. c. 70. %0a%0a28 See B. xxv. c. 94. %0a%0a30 See B. xxv. c. 102. %0a%0a32 See c. 29 of this Book. %0a34 See B. xxvii. c. 72. %0a%0a38 See c. 36 of this Book. %0a38 See c. 62 of this Book. %0a%0a%0a43. %0a%0a42 Iu B. xxii. c. 33. %0a%0a%0aChap. 89.] %0a%0a%0aREMEDIES FOR WARTS. %0a%0a%0a209 %0a%0a%0aand then beaten up with polenta, 43 and applied. For all kinds %0aof wounds apollinaris 44 is very useful. Root of astragalus, 45 %0areduced to powder, is good for running ulcers ; the same, too, %0awith callithrix, 46 boiled in water. For blisters, more particu¬ %0alarly when caused by the shoes, vervain is used, as also pounded %0alysimachia, 47 or nymphaea 48 dried and powdered; but when %0athey have assumed the form of inveterate ulcers, polythrix 48 %0awill be found more serviceable: %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 88.-POLYCNEMON : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aPolycnemon 50 is a plant which resembles cunila bubula ; 51 %0ait has a seed like that of pennyroyal, a ligneous stem with %0anumerous articulations, and odoriferous umbels, with a plea¬ %0asant though pungent smell. This plant is chewed and applied %0ato wounds inflicted with iron, the application being removed %0aat the end of four days. Symphyton 53 causes sores to cicatrize %0awith 