ins the hair. Ge- %0aranion , 8 taken in white wine, or hypocisthis 9 in red, arrests %0aall uterine discharges. Hyssop modifies hysterical suffocations. %0aLoot of vervain, taken in water, is a most excellent remedy %0afor all accidents incident to, or consequent upon, delivery. %0aSome persons mix bruised cypress seed with peucedanum 10 in %0ared wine. Seed, too, of psyllion , 11 boiled in water and taken %0awarm, has a soothing effect upon all defluxions of the uterus. %0aSymphjffon , 12 bruised in wine, promotes menstruation. Juice %0aof scordotis , 13 in the proportion of one drachma to four cyathi %0aof hydromel, accelerates delivery. Leaves of dittany are given %0afor the same purpose, in water, with remarkable success. It %0ais a well-known fact, too, that these leaves, to the extent of a %0asingle obolus even, will bring away the foetus instantaneously, %0aeven when dead, without the slightest inconvenience to the %0apatient. Pseudodictamnum 14 is productive of a somewhat %0asimilar effect, but not in so marked a degree: cyclaminos , 13 %0atoo, attached as an amulet; cissanthemos , 16 taken in drink; %0aand powdered betony, in hydromel. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 91. -ARSENOGONON : ONE MEDICINAL PROPERTY. THELY- %0a%0aGONON : ONE MEDICINAL PROPERTY. %0a%0aArsenogonon 17 and thelygonon are plants, both of them, %0a%0a%0a2 See B. xxv. c. 100. %0a%0a4 See B. xxv. c. 96. %0a%0a6 See B. xxii. c. 30, and B. xxv %0a6 See c. 68 of this Book. %0a%0a10 See B. xxv. c. 70. %0a%0a12 See B. xxvii. c. 24. %0a%0a14 See B. xxv. c. 53. %0a%0a16 See B. xxv. c. 68. %0a%0a17 These two plants, the names %0a%0a%0a3 See B. xxi. c. 29. %0a%0a5 See B. xxi. c. 103. %0a%0a56. 7 “ Albugines.” %0a%0a9 See c. 31 of this Book. %0a%0a11 See B. xxv. c. 90. %0a%0a13 See B. xxv. c. 27. %0a%0a13 See B. xxv. c. 67. %0a%0awhich signify “ begetting males,” %0a%0a%0a214 %0a%0a%0apliny’s natubal histoby. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVI. %0a%0a%0awith clusters resembling the blossoms of the olive, but paler, %0aand a white