diff:1673559149:1673559149:=1,4398d0%0a%3c BOOK XXVI. %0a%3c %0a%3c A CONTINUATION OF THE REMEDIES DERIVED FROM %0a%3c PLANTS, CLASSIFIED ACCORDING TO PARTICULAR %0a%3c DISEASES. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 1. (1.)—NEW FORMS OF DISF.ASE. %0a%3c %0a%3c The face of man has recently been sensible of new forms of %0a%3c disease, unknown 1 in ancient times, not only to Italy, but to %0a%3c almost the whole of Europe. Still, however, they have not as %0a%3c yet extended to the whole of Italy, nor have they made any %0a%3c very great inroads in Illyricum, Gaul, or Spain, or indeed %0a%3c any other parts, to so great an extent as in Rome and its en¬ %0a%3c virons. Though unattended with pain, and not dangerous to %0a%3c life, these diseases are of so loathsome a nature, that any form %0a%3c of death would be preferable to them. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 2.-THE NATURE OF LICHEN. %0a%3c %0a%3c The most insupportable of all these diseases is the one which, %0a%3c after its Greek appellation, is known to us as “ lichen.” 1 In %0a%3c consequence, however, of its generally making its first appear¬ %0a%3c ance at the chin, the Latins, by way of joke, originally— so %0a%3c prone are'maukind to make a jest of the misfortunes of others %0a%3c —gave it the name of “ mentagra ;” 2 an appellation which has %0a%3c since become established in general use. In many cases, how¬ %0a%3c ever, this disease spreads over the interior of the mouth, and %0a%3c takes possession of the whole face, with the sole exception of %0a%3c the eyes ; after which, it passes downwards to the neck, breast, %0a%3c and hands, covering them with foul furfuraceous eruptions. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 3.-AT WHAT PERIOB LICHEN FIRST MADE ITS APPEARANCE %0a%3c %0a%3c IN ITALY. %0a%3c %0a%3c This curse was unknown to the ancients, 3 and in the times of %0a%3c our fathers even, having first entered Italy in the middle of %0a%3c %0a%3c 1 Probably as Littre suggests, a peculiar form of elephantiasis, the %0a%3c leprosy of the middle ages. %0a%3c %0a%3c i The “chin disease from “ mentum,” tbe “ chin.” It is difficult to %0a%3c detect the joke which has here incurred the censure of our author. %0a%3c %0a%3c 3 Meaning the people of Italy. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 3.] WHEN LICHEN FIUST APPEAHED IN ITALY. 153 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c the reign of the Emperor Tiberius 4 * Claudius Caesar; where %0a%3c it was introduced from Asia, 4 * in which country it had lately %0a%3c made* its appearance, by a member of the equestrian order at %0a%3c Rome, a native of Perusium, secretary to the quaestor. The %0a%3c disease, however, did not attack either females or slaves, 6 7 %0a%3c nor yet the lower orders, or, indeed, the middle classes, but %0a%3c only the nobles, being communicated even by the momentary %0a%3c contact requisite for the act of salutation. 1 Many of those %0a%3c who persevered in undergoing a course of remedial treatment, %0a%3c though cured of the disease, retained scars upon the body more %0a%3c hideous even than the malady itself; it being treated with %0a%3c cauteries, as it was certain to break out afresh, unless means %0a%3c were adopted for burning it out of the body by cauterizing to %0a%3c the very bone. %0a%3c %0a%3c Upon this occasion several physicians repaired to Pome %0a%3c from Egypt, that fruitful parent of maladies of this nature, %0a%3c men who devoted themselves solely to this branch of medical %0a%3c practice; and very considerable were the profits they made. %0a%3c At all events, it is a well-known fact that Manilius Cornutus, %0a%3c a personage of praetorian rank, and legatus of the province of %0a%3c Aquitania, expended no less a sum than two hundred thou¬ %0a%3c sand 8 sesterces upon his cure. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is much more frequently, on the other hand, that we hear %0a%3c of new forms of diseases attacking the lower orders; a singular %0a%3c fact, and one quite unequalled for the marvellous phaenomena %0a%3c which sometimes attend these outbreaks. Thus, for instance, %0a%3c we find an epidemic suddenly making its appearance in a cer¬ %0a%3c tain country, and then confining itself, as though it had made %0a%3c its election so to do, to certain parts of the body, certain ages, %0a%3c and even certain pursuits in life. In the same way, too, while %0a%3c %0a%3c 4 It is somewhat difficult to say whether Tiberius, the predecessor, or %0a%3c Claudius, the successor of Caligula, is meant; most probably the latter, %0a%3c as the former’s reign would have been in the times of “ our fathers.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 4 * Asia Minor. %0a%3c %0a%3c 6 “ Cum apparuisset.” He is probably wrong here, for leprosy was %0a%3c known in Asia from the very earliest times. %0a%3c %0a%3c 6 This assertion as to the slaves and lower orders is somewhat doubtful, %0a%3c though it is very possible that the diet and habits of the higher orders %0a%3c umy have predisposed them more particularly for the attacks of the diseases. %0a%3c %0a%3c 7 “Osculi,” “kissing;” a nauseous and silly practice, still adhered to, %0a%3c between bearded men even, in many parts of Europe. %0a%3c %0a%3c 11 Upwards of £1500. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 154 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c one class of diseases attacks the young, another confines itself %0a%3c to adults ; while one malady extends itself only to the hightr %0a%3c classes, another is felt exclusively by the poor. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 4 .- CARBUNCLE. %0a%3c %0a%3c We find it stated in the Annals, that it was in the censorship 1 %0a%3c of L. Paulus and Q. Marcius that carbuncle 10 was first intro- %0a%3c duced into Italy, a malady which till then had confined itself %0a%3c solely to the province of Gallia Narbonensis. In the year %0a%3c in which I am writing these lines, two persons of consular %0a%3c rank have died of this disease, Julius Rufus 11 and Q. Lecanius %0a%3c Bassus ; 12 the former in consequence of an incision unskilfully %0a%3c made by his medical attendants, the latter through a wound %0a%3c upon the thumb of the left hand by pricking a carbuncle with %0a%3c a needle, a wound so small originally as to be hardly percep¬ %0a%3c tible. %0a%3c %0a%3c This disease makes its appearance in the more hidden 13 parts %0a%3c of the human, body, and mostly beneath the tongue. It ori¬ %0a%3c ginally has the form of a hard, red, pimple, with a blackish %0a%3c head mostly, though sometimes of a livid colour. It produces %0a%3c tension of the flesh, but unattended with swelling, pain, or %0a%3c any itching sensation ; indeed, the only symptom that accom¬ %0a%3c panies it is a confirmed drowsiness, which overpowers the pa- %0a%3c tient, and carries him off in the course of three days. Some¬ %0a%3c times, however, it is accompanied with shuddering, and small %0a%3c pustules about the sore ; and occasionally, though but rarely, %0a%3c with fever. When these symptoms extend to the fauces and %0a%3c oesophagus, death ensues with the greatest rapidity. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 5.-ELEPHANTIASIS. %0a%3c %0a%3c We have already 14 stated that elephantiasis 15 was unknown %0a%3c %0a%3c 3 a.u.c 590. %0a%3c %0a%3c 10 “ Carbunculus.” A malignant pustule, accompanied with swelling and %0a%3c ending with gangrene, is still known by this name, but it does not mani¬ %0a%3c fest any particular preference for the mouth and tongue. Fee says that %0a%3c carbuncle was recently (1833) endemic in Provence, the ancient’Gallia %0a%3c Narbonensis, for which reason it had received the name of “ Charbon Pro¬ %0a%3c vencal.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 11 Consul, A.u.c. 819. 12 Consul, a.u.c. 816. %0a%3c %0a%3c 13 Judging from this symptom, Dalechamps says that it looks more like %0a%3c chancre than carbuncle. u In B. xx. c. 52. %0a%3c %0a%3c 15 Supposed, as Pliny says, to have originally come from Upper Egypt. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. G.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c COLIC. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1 of) %0a%3c %0a%3c in Italy before the time of Pompeius Magnus. This malady, %0a%3c too, like those already mentioned, mostly makes its first ap¬ %0a%3c pearance in the face. In its primary form it bears a consider¬ %0a%3c able resemblance to a small lentil upon the nose; the skin %0a%3c gradually dries up all over the body, is marked with spots of %0a%3c various colours, and presents an unequal surface, being thick %0a%3c in one place, thin in another, indurated every here and there, %0a%3c and covered with a sort of rough scab. At a later period, the %0a%3c skin assumes a black hue, and compresses the flesh upon the %0a%3c bones, the fingers and toes becoming swollen. %0a%3c %0a%3c This disease was originally peculiar to Egypt. "Whenever it %0a%3c attacked the kings of that country, it was attended with pe¬ %0a%3c culiarly fatal effects to the people, it being the practice to %0a%3c temper their sitting-baths with human blood, for tbe treatment %0a%3c of the disease. As for Italy, however, its career was very %0a%3c soon cut short: the same was the case, too, with the disease %0a%3c known as “ gemursa” 16 to the ancients, a malady which made %0a%3c its appearance between the toes, and the very name of which is %0a%3c now buried in oblivion. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c chap. 6.—COLIC. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is a remarkable fact that some diseases should disappear %0a%3c from among us, while others, again, should continue to prevail, %0a%3c colic 17 for example. It was only in the reign of Tiberius %0a%3c Caesar that this malady made its appearance in Italy, the %0a%3c emperor himself being the first to be attacked by it; a cir¬ %0a%3c cumstance which produced considerable mystification through¬ %0a%3c out the City, when it read the edict issued by that prince %0a%3c excusing his inattention to public business, on the ground of his %0a%3c being laid up with a disease, the very name of which was till %0a%3c then unknown. To what cause are we to attribute these various %0a%3c diseases, or how is it that we have thus incurred the anger of %0a%3c the gods ? Was it deemed too little for man to be exposed to %0a%3c %0a%3c Lucretius, B. vi. 1. 1111, et seq ., attributes it to the water of the Nile. It %0a%3c is but rarely known in Europe. %0a%3c %0a%3c 16 Fee thinks that this may have been a sort of abscess similar to those %0a%3c between the fingers which are known as fourches by the French, and by %0a%3c medical men as “ Aposthema phalangum.” Gruner considers it to be a sort %0a%3c of Elephantiasis, and Triller identifies it with the disease called Gumretha %0a%3c by the Talmudists. %0a%3c %0a%3c 11 “ Colurn.” Fee takes this to be Schirrus of the colon. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c m %0a%3c %0a%3c 156 pliny’s natural history. [BoolXXYL %0a%3c %0a%3c fixed and determinate classes of maladies, already more than %0a%3c three hundred in number, that he must have new forms of %0a%3c disease to alarm him as well ? And then, in addition to all %0a%3c these, not less in number are the troubles and misfortunes which %0a%3c man brings upon himself! %0a%3c %0a%3c The remedies which I am here describing, are those which %0a%3c were universally employed in ancient times, Nature herself, %0a%3c so to say, making up the medicines: indeed, for a long time %0a%3c these were the only medicines employed. %0a%3c %0a%3c (2.) Hippocrates, 18 it is well known, was the first to com¬ %0a%3c pile a code of medical precepts, a thing which he did with the %0a%3c greatest perspicuity, as his treatises, we find, are replete with %0a%3c information upon the various plants. No less is the informa- %0a%3c tion which, we gain from the works of Diodes 19 of Carystus, %0a%3c second only in reputation, as well as date, to Hippocrates. %0a%3c The same, too, with reference to the works of Praxagoras, %0a%3c Chrysippus, and, at a later period, Erasistratus 20 of Cos. %0a%3c Herophilus 21 too, though himself the founder of a more refined %0a%3c system of medicine, was extremely profuse of his commenda¬ %0a%3c tions of the use of simples. At a later period, however, expe¬ %0a%3c rience, our most efficient instructor in all things, medicine in | %0a%3c particular, gradually began to be lost sight of in mere words %0a%3c and verbiage: it being found, in fact, much more agreeable %0a%3c to sit in schools, and to listen to the talk of a professor, than %0a%3c to go a simpling in the deserts, and to be searching for this %0a%3c plant or that at all the various seasons of the year. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 7. (3.)- THE NEW SYSTEM OF MEDICINE: ASCLEP1ADE3 %0a%3c %0a%3c THE PHYSICIAN. %0a%3c %0a%3c Still, however, the ancient theories remained unshaken, %0a%3c based as they were upon the still existing grounds of uni¬ %0a%3c versally acknowledged experience ; until, in the time of Pom- %0a%3c peius Magnus, Asclepiades, 22 a professor of rhetoric, who %0a%3c considered himself not sufficiently repaid by that pursuit, and %0a%3c whose readiness and sagacity rendered him better adapted for %0a%3c any other than forensic practice, suddenly turned his attention %0a%3c to the medical art. Having never practised medicine, and %0a%3c being totally unacquainted with the nature of remedies—a %0a%3c %0a%3c 18 See B. xxix. c. i. 13 See end of B. xx. %0a%3c %0a%3c 20 See B. xxix. c. 3. 21 See B. xxix. c. 5. %0a%3c %0a%3c 22 See end of B. vii. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 8.] CHANGES EFFECTED DY ASCLEPIADES. 157 %0a%3c %0a%3c knowledge only to be acquired by personal examination and %0a%3c actual experience—as a matter of course, he was obliged to %0a%3c renounce all previously-established theories, and to trust rather %0a%3c to his flowing periods and his well-studied discourses, for %0a%3c gaining an influence upon the minds of his audience. %0a%3c %0a%3c Reducing the whole art of medicine to an estimation solely %0a%3c of primary causes, he made it nothing but a merely con¬ %0a%3c jectural art, and established it as his creed, that there are five %0a%3c great principles of treatment for all diseases in common ; diet, %0a%3c use or non-use of wine, frictions, exercise on foot, and ex¬ %0a%3c ercise 23 in a carriage or on horseback. As every one perceived %0a%3c that each of these methods of treatment lay quite within his %0a%3c own reach, all, of course, with the greatest readiness gave %0a%3c their assent, willing as they were to believe that to be true %0a%3c which was so easy of acquisition; and hence it was that he %0a%3c attracted nearly all the world about him, as though he had %0a%3c been sent among mankind on a special mission from heaven. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 8. -THE CHANGES EFFECTED BY ASCLEPIADES IN THE %0a%3c %0a%3c PliACTICE OF MEDICINE. %0a%3c %0a%3c In addition to this, he had a wonderful tact in gaining the %0a%3c full confidence of his patients : sometimes he would make them %0a%3c a promise of wine, and then seize the opportune moment for %0a%3c administering it, while on other occasions, again, he would %0a%3c prescribe cold water: indeed, as Herophilus, among the an¬ %0a%3c cients, had been the first to enquire into the primary causes of %0a%3c disease, and Cleophantus had brought into notice the treat¬ %0a%3c ment of diseases by wine, so did Asclepiades, as we learn from %0a%3c M. V arro, prefer to be indebted for his surname and repute %0a%3c to the extensive use made by him of cold water as a %0a%3c remedy, lie employed also various other soothing remedies %0a%3c for his patients; thus, for instance, it was he that introduced %0a%3c swinging beds, the motion of which might either lull the %0a%3c malady, or induce sleep, as deemed desirable. It was he, %0a%3c too, that brought baths into such general use,—a method of %0a%3c treatment that was adopted -with the greatest avidity—in %0a%3c uddition to numerous other modes of treatment of a pleasant %0a%3c and soothing nature. By these means he acquired a great %0a%3c professional reputation, and a no less extended fame; which %0a%3c %0a%3c 23 “ Gestationesexercise on horseback, in a litter, or in a carriage %0a%3c drawn by horses. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 158 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c plint’s natural iustory. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XJYI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c was very considerably enhanced by the following incident: %0a%3c meeting the funeral procession of a person unknown to him, %0a%3c he ordered the body to be removed from the funeral pile 24 and %0a%3c carried home, and was thus the means of saving his life. This %0a%3c circumstance I am the more desirous to mention, that it may %0a%3c not be imagined that it was on slight grounds only that so %0a%3c extensive a revolution was effected in the medical art. %0a%3c %0a%3c There is, however, one thing, and one thing only, at which %0a%3c we have any ground for indignation,—the fact, that a single %0a%3c individual, and he belonging to the most frivolous nation 24 in %0a%3c the world, a man born in utter indigence, should all on a %0a%3c sudden, and that, too, for the sole purpose of increasing his %0a%3c income, give a new code of medical laws to mankind; laws, %0a%3c however, be it remembered, which have been annulled by %0a%3c numerous authorities since his day. The success of Asclepi- %0a%3c ades was considerably promoted by many of the usages of ancient %0a%3c medicine, repulsive in their nature, and attended with far too %0a%3c much anxiety : thus, for instance, it was the practice to cover %0a%3c up the patient with vast numbers of clothes, and to adopt %0a%3c every possible method of promoting the perspiration ; to order %0a%3c the body to be roasted before a fire; or else to be continually %0a%3c sending the patient on a search for sunshine, a thing hardly to %0a%3c be found in a showery climate like that of this city of ours; %0a%3c or rather, so to say, of the whole of Italy, so prolific 25 * as it is %0a%3c of fogs and rain. 26 It was to remedy these inconveniences, %0a%3c that he introduced the use of hanging baths, 27 an invention %0a%3c that was found grateful to invalids in the very highest %0a%3c degree. %0a%3c %0a%3c In addition to this, he modified the tortures which had %0a%3c hitherto attended the treatment of certain maladies; as in %0a%3c quinzv for instance, the cure of which before his time had been %0a%3c usually effected by the introduction of an instrument 28 into the %0a%3c throat. He condemned, and with good reason, the indiscrimi¬ %0a%3c nate use of emetics, which till then had been resorted to in a %0a%3c %0a%3c 21 See B. vii. c. 37. Apuleius gives the story at considerable length, in %0a%3c the Florida, B. iv. %0a%3c %0a%3c 25 Asia Minor. Asclepiades was a native of Prusa in Bithynia. %0a%3c %0a%3c as* yve adopt Sillig’s suggestion, and read “ nimborum altrice,” the %0a%3c word “ imperatrice ” being evidently out of place. The climate of Italy %0a%3c seems to have changed very materially since bis day. %0a%3c %0a%3c 26 See B. ii. c. 51. 27 See B. ix. c. 79. 26 “ Organo." %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 9.] REMARKS ON THE PRACTICES OF MAGIC. 159 %0a%3c %0a%3c most extraordinary degree. He disapproved also of the prac¬ %0a%3c tice of administering internally potions that are naturally %0a%3c injurious to the stomach, a thing that may truthfully be pro¬ %0a%3c nounced of the greater part of them. Indeed it will be as well %0a%3c to take an early opportunity of stating what are the medi¬ %0a%3c caments which, act beneficially upon the stomach. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 9. (4).- REMARKS IN DISPRAISE OF THE PRACTICES OF MAGIC. %0a%3c %0a%3c But above all things, it was the follies of magic more par¬ %0a%3c ticularly that contributed so essentially to his success—follies %0a%3c which had been carried to such a pitch as to destroy all confi¬ %0a%3c dence in the remedial virtues of plants. Thus, for instance, %0a%3c it was stoutly maintained that by the agency of the plant aethi- %0a%3c opis 29 rivers and standing waters could be dried up, and that by %0a%3c the very touch 30 * * * * all bars and doors might be opened : %0a%3c that if the plant achaemenis 31 were thrown into the ranks of the %0a%3c enemy it would be certain to create a panic and put them to %0a%3c flight: that latace 32 was given by the Persian kings to their %0a%3c ambassadors, to ensure them an abundant supply of every¬ %0a%3c thing wherever they might happen to be: with numerous %0a%3c other reveries of a similar nature. Where, I should like to %0a%3c know, were all these plants, when the Cimbri and Teutones %0a%3c brought upon us the horrors of warfare with their terrific yells ? %0a%3c or when Lucullus defeated, with a few legions, so many kings %0a%3c who ruled over the Magi ? 33 Why is it too that the Roman %0a%3c generals have always made it their first care in warfare to %0a%3c make provision for the victualling of their troops ? And how %0a%3c was it that at Pharsalia the troops of Caesar were suffering from %0a%3c famine, if an abundance of everything could have been ensured %0a%3c by the fortunate possession of a single plant ? Would it not have %0a%3c been better too for Scipio JEmilianus to have opened the gates %0a%3c of Carthage by touching them with a herb, than to have taken %0a%3c so many years to batter down its bulwarks with his engines of %0a%3c war? %0a%3c %0a%3c Turning to the present moment, let them, by the agency of %0a%3c the herb menu's, 3 * dry up the Pomp tine 35 Marshes, if they can, %0a%3c %0a%3c 29 See B. xxiv. c. 102. %0a%3c %0a%3c J,J We agree with Pintianus that the name of some plant here has been %0a%3c lost, the word ‘‘condiendis ” making no sense. %0a%3c %0a%3c 31 See B. xxiv. c. 102. %0a%3c %0a%3c 32 Some plant as fictitious as the others here mentioned. %0a%3c %0a%3c 33 See B. xxx. c. i. 31 See B. xxiv. c. 102. 33 See B. iii. c. 9. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c punt’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 160 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [nook 1XYI %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c and by these means restore so much territory to the regions of %0a%3c Italy in the neighbourhood of our city. In the works, too, of %0a%3c Democritus, already mentioned, 36 we find a recipe for the compo¬ %0a%3c sition of a medicament which will ensure the procreation of %0a%3c issue, both sure to be good and fortunate.—W hat king of Persia, %0a%3c pray, ever obtained that blessing ? It really would be a mar¬ %0a%3c vellous fact that human credulity, taking its rise originally in %0a%3c the very soundest of notions, should have ultimately arrived at %0a%3c such a pitch as this, if the mind of man understood, under any %0a%3c circumstances, how to keep within the bounds of modera¬ %0a%3c tion ; and if the very system of medicine thus introduced by %0a%3c Asclepiades, had not been carried to a greater pitch of extra¬ %0a%3c vagance than the follies of magic even, an assertion which %0a%3c I shall prove on a more appropriate occasion. 31 %0a%3c %0a%3c Such, however, is the natural constitution of the human %0a%3c mind, that, be the circumstances what they may, commencing %0a%3c with what is necessary it speedily arrives at the point of %0a%3c launching out in excess. %0a%3c %0a%3c We will now resume our account of the medicinal properties %0a%3c of the plants mentioned in the preceding Book, adding to our %0a%3c description such others as the necessities of the case may seem %0a%3c to require. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c chap. 10.—lichen: five remedies. %0a%3c %0a%3c As to the treatment of lichen, so noisome a disease as it is, %0a%3c we shall here give a number of additional remedies for it, %0a%3c gathered from all quarters, although those already described %0a%3c are by no means few in number. For the cure of lichea %0a%3c plantago is used, pounded, cinquefoil also, root of albucus 1 ® in %0a%3c combination with vinegar, the young shoots of the fig-tree %0a%3c boiled in vinegar, or roots of marsh-mallow boiled down to %0a%3c one-fourth with glue and vinegar. The sores are rubbed also %0a%3c with pumice, and then fomented with root of rumex 39 bruised %0a%3c in vinegar, or with scum of viscus 40 kneaded up with lime. A %0a%3c decoction, too, of tithymalos 41 with resin is highly esteemed for %0a%3c the same purpose. %0a%3c %0a%3c But to all these remedies the plant known as “ lichen,” fro® %0a%3c %0a%3c 36 In B. xxiv. c. 102. 37 In B. xxix. c. 5. %0a%3c %0a%3c 33 See B. xxi. c. 68. 39 See B. xx. c. 85. %0a%3c %0a%3c 40 “ Flos visci.” 41 See c. 39 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 12.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c SCROFULA. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 161 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c its efficacy as a cure, is held in preference. It is found grow¬ %0a%3c ing among rocks, and has a single broad leaf 42 near the root, %0a%3c and a single long stem, with small leaves hanging from it. %0a%3c This plant has the property also of effacing brand marks, %0a%3c being beaten up with honey for that purpose. There is another %0a%3c kind 43 of lichen also, which adheres entirely to rocks, like %0a%3c moss, and which is equally used as a topical application. The %0a%3c juice of it, dropt into wounds, or applied to abscesses, has the %0a%3c property of arresting haemorrhage: mixed with honey, it is %0a%3c curative of jaundice, the face and tongue being rubbed with %0a%3c it. Under this mode of treatment, the patient is recommended %0a%3c to wash in salt water, to anoint himself with oil of almonds, %0a%3c and to abstain from garden vegetables. For the cure of %0a%3c lichen, root of thapsia 44 is also used, bruised in honey. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 11.-QUINZY. %0a%3c %0a%3c For the treatment of quinzy, we find argemonia 48 recom¬ %0a%3c mended, in wine; a decoction of hyssop, boiled with figs, %0a%3c used as a gargle ; peucedanum , 46 with an equal proportion of %0a%3c sea-calf’s rennet; proserpinaca , 47 beaten up in the pickle of the %0a%3c mama 48 and oil, or else placed beneath the tongue; as also %0a%3c juice of cinquefoil, taken in doses of three cyathi. Used as a %0a%3c gargle, juice of cinquefoil is good for the cure of all affections %0a%3c of the fauces : verbascum , 49 too, taken in wine, is particularly %0a%3c useful for diseases of the to