ES. %0a%3c %0a%3c There is another bechion 74 also, known to some persons as %0a%3c “ salvia,” 75 and bearing a strong resemblance to verbascum. %0a%3c This plant is triturated, and the juice strained off and taken %0a%3c warm for cough and for pains in the side: it is considered %0a%3c very beneficial also for the stings of scorpions and sea- %0a%3c dragons. 76 It is a good plan, too, to rub the body with this %0a%3c juice, mixed with oil, as a preservative against the stings of %0a%3c serpents. A bunch of hyssop is sometimes boiled down with %0a%3c a quarter of a pound of honey, for the cure of cough. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 18. (7.)-AFFECTIONS OF THE SIDE, CHEST, AND 8T0MACH. %0a%3c %0a%3c For the cure of pains in the side and chest, verbascum 77 is %0a%3c used in water, with rue; powdered betony is also taken in %0a%3c warm water. Juice of seordotis 78 is used as a stomachic, %0a%3c %0a%3c 70 See B. xxiv. c. 85. %0a%3c %0a%3c 71 “Aquileges.” 72 See B. xxiv. c. 85. %0a%3c %0a%3c 73 Dried bechion, or coltsfoot, is still smoked by some persons for %0a%3c affections of the chest. %0a%3c %0a%3c 74 Generally identified with the Phlomos, or Verbascum lychnitis men¬ %0a%3c tioned in B. xxv. c. 74. 15 “ Sage.” See B. xxv. c. 73. %0a%3c %0a%3c 76 See B. ix. c. 43, and B. xxxii. c. 53. %0a%3c %0a%3c T* See B. xxv. c. 73. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 78 See B. xx. c. 27. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 19.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c MOLON OK 8YKOK. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 165 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c centaury also, gentian taken in water, and plantago, either %0a%3c eaten with the food, or mixed with lentils or a pottage of %0a%3c alica. 19 Betony, which is in general prejudicial to the stomach, %0a%3c is remedial for some stomachic affections, taken in drink or %0a%3c chewed, the leaves being used for the purpose. In a similar %0a%3c manner too, aristolochia 80 is taken in drink, or dried agaric is %0a%3c chewed, a draught of undiluted wine being taken every now %0a%3c and then. Nymphaea heraclia 81 is also applied topically in %0a%3c these cases, and juice of peucedanum. 82 For burning pains in %0a%3c the stomach psyllion 83 is applied, or else cotyledon 84 beaten up %0a%3c with polenta, or aizoiim. 85 %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 19.-MOLON OK SYRON. AMOMUM. %0a%3c %0a%3c Molon 96 is a plant with a striated stem, a soft diminutive %0a%3c leaf, and a root four fingers in length, at the extremity of %0a%3c which there is a head like that of garlic ; by some persons it %0a%3c is known as “ syron.” Taken in wine, it is curative of affec¬ %0a%3c tions of the stomach, and of hardness of breathing. For similar %0a%3c purposes the greater centaury is used, in an electuary ; juice %0a%3c also of plantago, or else the plant itself, eaten with the food; %0a%3c pounded betony, in the proportion of one pound to half an %0a%3c ounce of Attic honey, taken daily in warm water ; and aristo¬ %0a%3c lochia 81 or agaric, taken in doses of three oboli, in warm water %0a%3c or asses’ milk. %0a%3c %0a%3c For hardness of breathing an infusion of cissanthemos 88 is %0a%3c taken in drink, and for the same complaint, as also for asthma, %0a%3c hyssop. For pains in the liver, chest, and side, if unattended %0a%3c with fever, juice of peucedanum is used. For spitting of %0a%3c blood agaric is employed, in doses of one victoriatus, 89 bruised %0a%3c and administered in five cyathi of honied wine: amomum, 90 %0a%3c too, is equally useful for that purpose. For liver diseases in %0a%3c %0a%3c 79 See B. xviii. c. 29. Fee observes that none of these prescriptions %0a%3c would be countenanced at the present day. %0a%3c %0a%3c 80 See B. xxv. c. 54. 81 See B. xxv. c. 37. %0a%3c %0a%3c 82 See B. xxv. c. 70. 83 See B. xxv. c. 90. %0a%3c %0a%3c M See B. xxv. c. 101. 85 See B. xxv. c. 102. %0a%3c %0a%3c 86 Possibly the same plant as the “ Moly ” of B. xxv. c. 8. If so, as %0a%3c Fee says, it would appear to belong to the genus Allium, or garlic. %0a%3c %0a%3c 87 See B. xxv. c. 84. 88 See B. xxv. c. 68. %0a%3c %