c sea-shore against which the waves break, springing up, so to %0a%3c say, neither upon dry land nor in the sea. The leaves are %0a%3c like those of isatis, 2 only thicker ; the stem is a palm in height %0a%3c and divided at the extremity, and the root white, thick, and %0a%3c odoriferous, with a warm flavour; it is recommended for %0a%3c diseases of the liver, boiled with spelt. This plant is thought %0a%3c by some to be identical with polium, of which we have already %0a%3c spoken in the appropriate place. 3 %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 23.-THE GROMPH^NA. %0a%3c %0a%3c Gromphaena 4 is the name of a plant, the stem of which is %0a%3c covered with leaves of a green and rose colour, arranged alter¬ %0a%3c nately. The leaves of it are administered in oxycrate, in %0a%3c cases of spitting of blood. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 24.-THE MALUNDRUM : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c For diseases of the liver the malundrum 5 is prescribed, a %0a%3c %0a%3c 69 In It. xxv. c. 48. %0a%3c %0a%3c 1 Sprengel identifies it with the Plumbago of B. xxv. c. 22. Fde is %0a%3c not of that opinion, and agrees with Matthioli in considering it to be the %0a%3c Aster tripolium of Linnaeus, the Sea starwort. Littre gives the Statice %0a%3c limonium of Linnajus. %0a%3c %0a%3c 2 See B. xx. c. 25. 3 In B. xxi. c. 21. %0a%3c %0a%3c 4 Sprengel and Dcsfontaines identify it with the Amaranthus tricolor ; %0a%3c Fee is strongly of opinion that it has not been correctly identified. %0a%3c %0a%3c 4 Clusius and Sprengel identify it with the Lychnis silvestris of Lin¬ %0a%3c naeus, the Wild lychnis or Viscous catchfly. Fee considers it to be uu- %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 168 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural hibtoky. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c plant which grows in meadows and corn-fields, with a white %0a%3c odoriferous flower. The stem is diminutive, and is beaten up %0a%3c in old wine. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 25.-CHALCEXUM ; TWO REMEDIES. MOLEMONITJM ; %0a%3c %0a%3c ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c Chalcetum* 