me to us than any other part of the body, is ever craving, %0a%3c like some importunate creditor, and makes its calls repeatedly %0a%3c in the day. It is for its sake, more particularly, that avarice %0a%3c is so insatiate, for its sake that luxury is so refined, 22 for its sake %0a%3c that men voyage to the shores even of the Phasis, for its sake %0a%3c that the very depths of the ocean are ransacked. And yet, %0a%3c with all this, no one ever gives a thought how abject is the %0a%3c condition of this part of our body, how disgusting the results %0a%3c ot its action upon what it has received ! No wonder then, %0a%3c %0a%3c 18 For the identity of this plant, see B. xxvii. c. 24. %0a%3c %0a%3c 17 See B. xix. c. 50, and B. xx. c. 61. %0a%3c %0a%3c 19 See B. xxiv. c. 80. 19 See c. 18 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c 3 " Identified with the Lavendula stoechas of Linnaeus, the French lavender. %0a%3c %0a%3c 21 “ ' as.” 22 In search of pheasants. See B. vi. c. 4, %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny's natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 170 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c that the belly should have to be indebted to the aid of medicine %0a%3c in the very highest degree ! %0a%3c %0a%3c Scordotis, 23 fresh-gathered and beaten up, in doses of one %0a%3c drachma, with wine, arrests flux of the bowels; an effect %0a%3c equally produced by a decoction of it taken in drink. Pole- %0a%3c monia, 24 too, is given in wine for dysentery, or two fingers’ %0a%3c length of root of verbascum, 25 in water; seed of nymphaea %0a%3c heraclia, 26 in wine ; the upper root of xiphion, 27 in doses of one %0a%3c drachma, in vinegar; seed of plantago, beaten up in wine; %0a%3c plantago itself boiled in vinegar, or else a pottago of alicu 2 * %0a%3c mixed with the juice of the plant; plantago boiled with %0a%3c lentils ; plantago dried and powdered, and sprinkled in drink, %0a%3c with parched poppies pounded; juice of plantago, used as an %0a%3c injection, or taken in drink ; or betony taken in wine heated %0a%3c with a red-hot iron. For coeliac affections, betony is taken in %0a%3c astringent wine, or iberis is applied topically, as already 29 %0a%3c stated. For tenesmus, root of nymphaea heraclia is taken in %0a%3c wine, or else psyllion 30 in water, or a decoction of root of %0a%3c acoron. 31 Juice of aizoiim 32 arrests diarrhoea and dysentery, and %0a%3c expels round tape-worm. Root of Symphytum, 33 taken in wine, %0a%3c arrests diarrhoea and dysentery, and daucus 34 has a similar %0a%3c effect. Leaves of aizoum 33 beaten up in wine, and dried %0a%3c alcea 36 powdered and taken in wine, are curative of griping %0a%3c pains in the bowels. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c chap. 29. —the astragalus: six remedies. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Astragalus 37 is the name of a plant which has long leaves, %0a%3c with numerous incisions, and running aslant near the root. %0a%3c The stems are three or four in number, and covered with leaves: %0a%3c the flower is like that of the hyacinth, and the roots are red, %0a%3c hairy, matted, and remarkably hard. It grows on stony local- %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 23 See B. xxv. c. 27. %0a%3c %0a%3c 25 See B. xxv. c. 73. %0a%3c %0a%3c 21 See B. xxv. c. 89. %0a%3c %0a%3c 29 In B. xxv. c. 84. %0a%3c %0a%3c 31 See B. xxv. c. 100. %0a%3c 33 See B. xxvii. c. 24. %0a%3c 35 See Note 32 above. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 24 See B. xxv. c. 28. %0a%3c 26 See B. xxv. c. 37. %0a%3c 28 See B. xviii. c. 29. %0a%3c 30 See B. xxv. c. 90. %0a%3c 32 See B. xxv. c. 102. %0a%3c 34 See B. xxv. c. 84. %0a%3c See B. xxvii. c. 6. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 31 Sprengel identifies it with the Phaca Baetica, Spanish bastard vetch; %0a%3c hut the flowers of that plant, as Fee remarks, are yellow. He consider? %0a%3c it to he the Lathyrus tuberosus of Linnaeus, the Pease earth-nut. Littre %0a%3c gives the Orobus sessilifolius of Sibthorp. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 30.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c LADANUM. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c in %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ities, equally exposed to the sun and to falls of snow, those in %0a%3c the vicinity of l’heneus in Arcadia, for instance. Its proper¬ %0a%3c ties are highly astringent; the root of it, taken in wine, arrests %0a%3c looseness of the bowels, having the additional effect of throw¬ %0a%3c ing downward the aqueous humours, and so acting as a diuretic; %0a%3c a property, in fact, which belongs>to most substances which %0a%3c act astringently upon the bowels. %0a%3c %0a%3c Bruised in red 37 * wine, this plant is curative of dysentery ; %0a%3c it is only bruised, however, with the greatest difficulty. It is %0a%3c extremely useful, also, as a fomentation for gum-boils. The %0a%3c end of autumn is the time for gathering it, after the leaves ai’e %0a%3c off; it being then left to dry in the shade. %0a%3c %0a%3c CIIAP. 30.- LADANUM : EIGHTEEN REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Diarrhoea may be also arrested by the use of either kind of %0a%3c ladanum. 38 The kind which is found in corn-fields is pounded %0a%3c for this purpose, and then passed through a sieve, being taken %0a%3c either in hydromel, or in wine of the highest quality. “Ledon” %0a%3c is the name of the plant from which ladanum 39 is obtained in %0a%3c Cyprus, it being found adhering to the beard of the goats %0a%3c there; the most esteemed, however, is that of Arabia. 40 At %0a%3c the present day, it is prepared in Syria and Africa also, being %0a%3c known as “ toxicum,” from the circumstance that ingathering %0a%3c it, they pass over the plant a bow, 41 with the string stretched, %0a%3c and covered with wool, to which the dewlike flocks of lada¬ %0a%3c num adhere. We have described it at further length, when %0a%3c treating of the perfumes. 42 %0a%3c %0a%3c This substance has a very powerful odour, and is hard in the %0a%3c extreme; for, in fact, there is a considerable quantity of earth %0a%3c adhering to it: it is most esteemed when in a pure state, %0a%3c aromatic, soft, green, and resinous. It is of an emollient, %0a%3c desiccative, and ripening nature, and acts as a narcotic : it pre¬ %0a%3c vents the hair from falling off, and preserves its dark colour. In %0a%3c combination Aviih hydromel or oil of roses, it is used as an %0a%3c %0a%3c ,7 * “ Rubrum,” and not “ nigrum,” which Avas also what we call “ red ” %0a%3c wine. %0a%3c %0a%3c 38 F6e is unable to identify it. The Galeopsis ladanum of Linnaeus, %0a%3c the Red dead-nettle, has been suggested, but on insufficient grounds, pro¬ %0a%3c bably. 39 See B. xii. c. 37. %0a%3c %0a%3c 40 It is still brought from the islands of Greece, but no longer from %0a%3c Arabia. 41 T o'£bv. %0a%3c %0a%3c 42 In B. xii. c. 37. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 172 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c print's natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c injection for the ears; with the addition of salt, it is employed %0a%3c for the cure of furfuraceous eruptions of the skin, and for run¬ %0a%3c ning ulcers. Taken with storax, it is good for chronic cough; %0a%3c it is also extremely efficacious as a carminative. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 31. -CHONDRIS OR PS^UDODICTAMNON : ONE REMEDY. HYPO- %0a%3c %0a%3c CISTHIS OR OROBETHRON ; TWO VARIETIES : EIGHT REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Chondris, too, or pseudodictamnon, 43 acts astringently on the %0a%3c bowels. Hypocisthis, 44 by some known also as “ orobethron,” %0a%3c is similar to an unripe pomegranate in appearance; it grows, %0a%3c as already stated, 46 beneath the cisthus, whence its name. %0a%3c Dried in the shade, and taken in astringent, red wine, these %0a%3c plants arrest diarrhoea—for there are two kinds of hypocisthis, %0a%3c it must be remembered, the white and the red. It is the juice %0a%3c of the plant that is used, being of an astringent, desiccative, %0a%3c nature : that of the red kind, however, is the best for fluxes %0a%3c of the stomach. Taken in drink, in doses of three oboli, with %0a%3c amylum, 46 it arrests spitting of blood ; and, employed either as %0a%3c a potion or as an injection, it is useful for dysentery. Vervain, %0a%3c too, is good for similar complaints, either taken in water, or, %0a%3c when there are no symptoms of fever, in Aminean 47 wine, the %0a%3c proportion being five spoonfuls to three cyathi of wine. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 32. -LAVER 0^ SION : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Laver, 48 too, a plant which grows in streams, preserved and %0a%3c boiled, is curative of griping pains in the bowels. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 33. -POTAMOGITON: EIGHT REMEDIES. THE 8TATICE : %0a%3c %0a%3c THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Potamogiton, 49 too, taken in wine, is useful for dysentery %0a%3c and cceliac affections : it is a plant similar to beet in the leaves, %0a%3c but smaller and more hairy, and rising but little above the %0a%3c surface of the water. It is the leaves that are used, being of %0a%3c a refreshing, astringent nature, and particularly good for %0a%3c diseases of the legs, and, with honey or vinegar, for corrosive %0a%3c ulcers. %0a%3c %0a%3c 45 “ False-dittany,” or “ bastard dittany.” See B. xxv. c. 53. %0a%3c %0a%3c 44 The Cytinus hypocisthis of Linnaeus. %0a%3c %0a%3c 45 In B. xxiv. c. 28. 46 See B. xviii. c. 17, and B.xxii. c. 67. %0a%3c %0a%3c 47 See B. xiv. c. 5. 49 The Sium of B. xxii. c. 41. %0a%3c %0a%3c 49 Probably the Potamogeton natans of Linnaeus, Broad-leaved pond- %0a%3c weed, or some kindred plant. Its name signifies “ the neighbour of rivers.” %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 34.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE CERATIA. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 173 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Castor has given a different description of this plant. Ac¬ %0a%3c cording to him, it has a smaller leaf, 50 like horse-hair, 61 with a %0a%3c long, smooth, stem, and grows in watery localities. With the %0a%3c root of it he used to treat scrofulous sores and indurations. %0a%3c Potamogiton neutralizes the effects of the bite of the crocodile; %0a%3c hence it is that those who go in pursuit of that animal, are in %0a%3c the habit of carrying it about them. %0a%3c %0a%3c Achillea 62 also arrests looseness of the bowels ; an effect %0a%3c equally produced by the statice, 63 a plant with seven heads, like %0a%3c those of the rose, upon as many stems. %0a%3c %0a%3c CUAP. 34. - THE CERATIA : TWO REMEDIES. LEONTOPODION, XET7- %0a%3c %0a%3c CEORON, DORIPETRON, OR THORYBETHRON. LAGOPUS : THREE %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The ceratia 64 is a plant with a single 55 leaf, and a large %0a%3c knotted root: taken with the food, it is curative of coeliac %0a%3c affections and dysentery. *■ %0a%3c %0a%3c Leontopodion, 66 a plant known also as “ leuceoron,” “ dori- %0a%3c petron,” or “ thorybethron,” has a root which acts astringently %0a%3c upon the bowels and carries off bile, being taken in doses of %0a%3c two denarii in hydromel. It grows in champaign localities %0a%3c with a poor soil: the seed, taken in drink, produces night-mare, 57 %0a%3c it is said, in the sleep. %0a%3c %0a%3c Lagopus 68 arrests diarrhoea, taken in wine, or, if there are %0a%3c symptoms of fever, in water. This plant is attached to the %0a%3c groin, for tumours in that part of the body: it grows in corn¬ %0a%3c fields. Many persons recommend, in preference to anything else, %0a%3c %0a%3c 50 C. Bauhin and Sprengcl identify the plant here described with the %0a%3c Potamogeton pusillum of Linnaeus; but Fee considers it extremely doubtful. %0a%3c %0a%3c 61 A species of Equisetum would seem to be meant; indeed, Littre gives %0a%3c the Equisetum telmateia. 52 See B. xxv. c. 19. %0a%3c %0a%3c M Fee thinks that this may possibly be the Statice Armeria of Linnams, %0a%3c Sea thrift, or Sea gilly-flower. %0a%3c %0a%3c M Considered by Sprengel to be the Cyclaminos chamsecissos of B. xxv. %0a%3c c. 69, which he identifies with the Convallaria bifolia of Linnaeus, the %0a%3c Little lily of the valley, or May lily. Fabius Columna and Brotero con¬ %0a%3c sider it to be the Dentaria trifolia, Three-leaved toothwort. %0a%3c %0a%3c 55 This is incorrect, if it is the Lily of the valley. %0a%3c %0a%3c M “ Lion’s paw,” “white plant,” or “rock-spear.” Probably the %0a%3c Leontice leontopetalum of Linnaeus, Lion’s paw, or Lion’s leaf. See B. %0a%3c xivii. c. 72. 47 “ Lymphatica somnia.” %0a%3c %0a%3c ^ “Hare’s foot.” Possibly the Trifolium arvense of Linnaeus, Hare’s %0a%3c foot trefoil. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 174 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLINY’S natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XIYL %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c for desperate cases of dysentery, a decoction of roots of cinque¬ %0a%3c foil in milk, or else aristolochia, 69 in the proportion of one %0a%3c victoriatus 60 to three cyathi of wine. In the case of the pre¬ %0a%3c parations above-mentioned, which are recommended to be taken %0a%3c warm, it will be the best plan to heat them with a red-hot %0a%3c iron. %0a%3c %0a%3c On the other hand, again, the juice of the smaller centaury %0a%3c acts as a purgative upon the bowels, and carries off bile, taken, %0a%3c in doses of one drachma, in one hemina of water with a little %0a%3c salt and vinegar. The greater centaury is curative of griping %0a%3c pains in the bowels. Betony, also, has a laxative effect, taken %0a%3c in the proportion of four drachmae to nine cyathi of hydromel: %0a%3c the same, too, with euphorbia 61 or agaric, taken, in doses of two %0a%3c drachma), with a little salt, in water, or else in three oboli of %0a%3c honied wine. Cyclaminos, 63 also, is a purgative, either taken %0a%3c in water or used as a suppository; the same, too, with chamje- %0a%3c cissos, 66 employed as a suppository. A handful of hyssop, %0a%3c boiled down to one third with salt, or beaten up with oxymel %0a%3c and salt, and applied to the abdomen, promotes pituitous %0a%3c evacuations, and expels intestinal worms. Root also of peu- %0a%3c cedanum 64 carries off pituitous humours and bile. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 35. -EPITHYMON OR HIPPOPHEOS : EIGHT REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The two kinds of anagallis, taken in hydromel, are purgative; %0a%3c the same, too, with epithymon, 68 which is the blossom of a %0a%3c sort 66