nt wine. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 36. -rYCNOCOMON ; FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Pycnocomon, 71 too, is a purgative. It is a plant with leaves %0a%3c like those of rocket, only thicker and more acrid ; the root is %0a%3c round, of a yellow colour, and with an earthy smell. The %0a%3c stem is quadrangular, of a moderate length, thin, and sur¬ %0a%3c mounted with a flower like that of ocimum. 72 It is found %0a%3c growing in rough stony soils. The root, taken in doses of two %0a%3c denarii in hydromel, acts as a purgative upon the bowels, %0a%3c and effectually carries off bile and pituitous humours. The %0a%3c seed, taken in doses of one drachma in wine, is productive of %0a%3c dreams and restlessness. Capnos, 73 too, carries off bile by the %0a%3c urine. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 37. —POLYPODION : THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Polypodion, 74 known to us by the name of “ filicula,” hears %0a%3c some resemblance to fern. The root of it is used medicinally ; %0a%3c %0a%3c 68 See B. xxi. c. 19. %0a%3c %0a%3c 89 It has a root originally, but the root withers as soon as it has attached %0a%3c itself to the stem of the plant to which it clings. %0a%3c %0a%3c 10 Sec B. xxv. c. 37. Holland says, on the contrary, that it is a binding %0a%3c plant. %0a%3c %0a%3c 71 “ Thick hair.” It is generally identified with the Leonurus mar- %0a%3c rnbiastrum of Linnaeus. Columna makes it to be the Scabiosa succisa of %0a%3c Linnaeus, the Devil’s bit scabious, and Brunsfeld the Angelica silvestris of %0a%3c Linnaeus, Wild angelica. %0a%3c %0a%3c 73 See B. xxi. c. 60. 73 See B. xxv. c. 98. %0a%3c %0a%3c 74 “ Many-footed.” The Polypodium vulgare of Linnaeus, the Common %0a%3c polypody. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 176 punt’s NATURAL HISTORY. [Book XXVI. %0a%3c %0a%3c being fibrous, and of a grass green colour within, about the %0a%3c thickness of the little finger, and covered with cavernous %0a%3c suckers like those on the arms of the polypus. 1 his plant is of %0a%3c a sweetish 15 taste, and is found growing among rocks and under %0a%3c trees. The root is steeped in water, and the juice extracted; %0a%3c sometimes, too, it is cut in small pieces and sprinkled upon %0a%3c cabbage, beet, mallows, or salt meat; or else it is boiled with %0a%3c pap, 76 as a gentle aperient for the bowels, in cases of fever even. %0a%3c It carries off bile also and the pituitous' humours, but nets %0a%3c injuriously upon the stomach. Dried and powdered and ap¬ %0a%3c plied to the nostrils, it cauterizes polypus 17 of the nose. It has %0a%3c neither seed 18 nor flower. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 38.- SCAMMONY ; EIGHT REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Scammony, 19 also, is productive of derangement of the %0a%3c stomach. It carries off bile, and acts strongly as a purgative %0a%3c upon the bowels; unless, indeed, aloes are added, in the propor¬ %0a%3c tion of two drachmae of aloes to two oboli of scammony. The %0a%3c drug thus called is the juice of a plant that is branchy from %0a%3c the root, and has unctuous, white, triangular, leaves, with %0a%3c a solid, moist root, of a nauseous flavour: it grows in nch %0a%3c white soils. About the period of the rising of the Dog- %0a%3c star, an excavation is made about the root, to let the juice %0a%3c collect: which done, it is dried in the sun and divided into %0a%3c tablets. The root itself, too, or the outer coat of it, is some¬ %0a%3c times dried. The scammony most esteemed is that of Colophon, %0a%3c Mysia, and Priene. In appearance it ought to be smooth and %0a%3c shiny, and as much like bull glue as possible : it should present %0a%3c a fungous surface also, covered with minute holes ; should melt %0a%3c with the greatest rapidity, have a powerful smell, and be sticky %0a%3c like gum. "When touched with the tongue, it should give out %0a%3c a white milky liquid; it ought also to be extremely light, and %0a%3c to turn white when melted. %0a%3c %0a%3c 75 It is for this reason that it is called “ reglisse,” or “ liquorice,” in %0a%3c some parts of 