eived drops. While the juice is being collected, due %0a%3c care must be taken not to let it touch the eyes. From the leaves, %0a%3c pounded, a juice is also extracted, but not of so useful a %0a%3c nature as the other kind: a decoction, too, is made from the %0a%3c branches. %0a%3c %0a%3c The seed also is used, being boiled with honey and made up %0a%3c into purgative 86 pills. These seeds are sometimes inserted in %0a%3c hollow teeth with wax : the teeth are rinsed too, with a de¬ %0a%3c coction of the root in wine or oil. The juice is used externally %0a%3c for lichens, and is taken internally both as an emetic and to %0a%3c promote alvine evacuation : in other respects, it is prejudicial to %0a%3c the stomach. Taken in drink, with the addition of salt, it car¬ %0a%3c ries off pituitous humours; and in combination with saltpetre,** %0a%3c removes bile. In cases where it is desirable that it should purge %0a%3c by stool, it is taken with oxycrate, but where it is wanted %0a%3c to act as an emetic, with raisin wine or hydromel; three oboli %0a%3c being a middling dose. The best method, however, of using it, %0a%3c is to eat the prepared figs above-mentioned, just after taking %0a%3c food. In taste, it is slightly burning to the throat; indeed it %0a%3c is of so heating a nature, that, applied externally by itself, it %0a%3c raises blisters on the flesh, like those caused by the action of %0a%3c fire. Hence it is that it is sometimes employed as a cautery. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 40.— THE TITHYMALOS MYRTITES, OR CARY1TES ; TWK5TT- %0a%3c ONE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c A second kind of tithymalos is called “ myrtites M87 by some %0a%3c persons, and “ caryites ” by others. It has leaves like those %0a%3c of myrtle, pointed and prickly, but with a softer surface, and %0a%3c grows, like the one already mentioned, in rugged soils. The %0a%3c tufted heads of it are gathered just as barley is beginning to %0a%3c swell in the ear, and, after being left for nine days in the shade, 