ne, if %0a%3c there are no symptoms of fever, or the seed of it being ad¬ %0a%3c ministered in red wine; a good handful of vervain also, boiled %0a%3c down in water to one half. But of all the remedies for this %0a%3c disease, juice of chamaeacte 95 is looked upon as bjr far the most %0a%3c efficacious. %0a%3c %0a%3c Morbid or pituitous eruptions are cured by the agency of %0a%3c plantago, or else root of cyclaminos 96 with honey. Leaves of %0a%3c ebulum, 97 bruised in old wine and applied topically, are curative %0a%3c of the disease called “ boa,” which makes its appearance in %0a%3c the form of red pimples. Juice of strychnos, 98 applied as a %0a%3c liniment, is curative of prurigo. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CUAP. 74. -REMEDIES FOR ERYSIPELAS. %0a%3c %0a%3c For the cure of erysipelas, aizoum" is used, or else pounded %0a%3c leaves of hemlock, or root of mandragora ; 3 this last being cut %0a%3c into round slices like cucumber and suspended over must, 2 after %0a%3c which it is hung up in the smoke, and then pounded in wine %0a%3c or vinegar. It is a good plan too to use fomentations with %0a%3c myrtle w'ine : two ounces of mint beaten up in vinegar with %0a%3c one ounce of live sulphur, form a mixture sometimes employed; %0a%3c as also soot mixed with vinegar. %0a%3c %0a%3c There are several kinds of erysipelas, one in particular %0a%3c which attacks the middle of the body, and is known as %0a%3c “zoster:” 3 should it entirely surround the body, its effects are %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c •* See B. xxv. c. 90. %0a%3c %0a%3c 90 See B. xxv. c. 101. %0a%3c %0a%3c 92 See c. 44 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c M See B. xxv. c. 71. %0a%3c %0a%3c 96 See B. xxv. c. 67. %0a%3c %0a%3c 98 See B. xxi. c. 105. %0a%3c %0a%3c 1 See B. xxv. c. 94. %0a%3c %0a%3c 3 The “ belt ”—known to us as %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 69 See B. xxv. c. 92. %0a%3c %0a%3c 91 See B. xxv. c. 71. %0a%3c %0a%3c 93 See c. 54 of this Book. %0a%3c 95 See B. xxv. c. 71. %0a%3c r ‘ See B. xxv. c. 71. %0a%3c %0a%3c 99 See B. xxv. 