%3c using juice of cinquefoil, in doses of three cyathi, with salt %0a%3c and honey. Boot of cyclaminos 11 is also taken in drink in %0a%3c doses of three drachmae, the patient sitting in a warm room %0a%3c free from all cold and draughts, the infusion expelling the %0a%3c bile by its action as a sudorific. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 4 See B. xxv. c. 39. %0a%3c %0a%3c 6 See B. xxv. c. 66. %0a%3c %0a%3c 8 See B. xxv. c. 102. %0a%3c %0a%3c 10 See c. 37 of this Book. %0a%3c 12 See B. xxv. c. 39. %0a%3c %0a%3c 14 See B. xxv. c. 107. %0a%3c %0a%3c 16 See B. xxv. c. 3'J. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 5 See B. xxxv. c. 57. %0a%3c %0a%3c I See B. xxv. c. 101. %0a%3c 9 See B. xxv. c. 18. %0a%3c %0a%3c II See B. xxv. c. 90. %0a%3c 13 See B. xxv. c. 73. %0a%3c 13 B. iv. cc. 62, 64. %0a%3c %0a%3c 17 See B. xxv. c. 67. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 'hap. 79.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDIES FOE ABSCESSES. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 201 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Leaves of tussilago 18 are also used in water for this purpose ; %0a%3c the seed of either kind of linozostis, 19 sprinkled in the drink, or %0a%3c made into a decoction with chick-pease or wormwood : hyssop %0a%3c berries taken in water; the plant lichen,'- 0 all other vege¬ %0a%3c tables being carefully abstained from while it is being used; %0a%3c polythrix, 21 taken in wine; and struthion, 22 in honied wine. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 77. -KEMEDIES FOE BOILS. %0a%3c %0a%3c There are boils also, known as “ furunculi,” 23 which make %0a%3c their appearunce indiscriminately on all parts of the body, and %0a%3c are productive of the greatest inconvenience: sometimes %0a%3c indeed, when the constitution is exhausted, they are fatal in %0a%3c their effects. For their cure, leaves of pycnocomon 24 are em¬ %0a%3c ployed, beaten up with polenta, 25 if the boil has not come to a %0a%3c bead. They are dispersed also by an application of leaves of %0a%3c ephedron. 26 %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 78. -EEMEDIES FOE FISTULA. %0a%3c %0a%3c Fistulas, too, insidiously attack all parts of