 83. (13.) -HIPPURIS, OTHERWISE CALLED EPBEDRON, %0a%3c %0a%3c ANABASIS, OR EQUISJ3TUM ; THREE KINDS OF IT : EIGHTEEN %0a%3c REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Equisaetum, a plant called “ hippuris” by the Greeks, and %0a%3c which we have mentioned in terms of condemnation, when %0a%3c treating of meadow lands 72 —it being, in fact, a sort of hair of %0a%3c the earth, similar in appearance to horse-hair 75 —is used by %0a%3c runners for the purpose of diminishing 74 the spleen. For this %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 61 See c. 53 of this Book. 62 See B. xxv. c. 76. %0a%3c %0a%3c 63 See Note 49 above. 64 Our peony. See B. xxv. c. 10. %0a%3c %0a%3c 65 See B. xxv. c. 33. 66 See B. xxv. c. 35. %0a%3c %0a%3c 67 See B. xxv. c. 39. 68 See B. xxv. c. 102. %0a%3c %0a%3c 69 See c. 29 of the present Book. 70 See B. xxv. c. 45. %0a%3c %0a%3c 71 See B. xxv. c. 19. %0a%3c %0a%3c 79 In B. xviii. c. 67 ; where it is called “ equiscetis.” M. Fraas identifies %0a%3c it with the Equisaetum limosum of Linnaeus. %0a%3c %0a%3c 73 Whence its name “ equisaetum.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 71 See B. xi. c. 30. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 204 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c purpose it is boiled down in a new earthen vessel to one third, %0a%3c the vessel being filled to the brim, and the decoction taken %0a%3c in doses of one hemina for three successive days. It is strictly %0a%3c forbidden, however, to eat any food of a greasy nature the day %0a%3c before taking it. %0a%3c %0a%3c Among the Greeks there are various opinions in relation to %0a%3c this plant. According to some, who give it the same name of %0a%3c “ hippuris,” it has leaves like those of the pine tree, and of a %0a%3c swarthy hue; and, if we are to believe them, it is possessed of %0a%3c virtues of such a marvellous nature, that if touched by the %0a%3c patient only, it will arrest haemorrhage. Some authorities call it %0a%3c “hippuris,’’others, again, “ ephedron,” and others “anabasis;” %0a%3c and they tell us that it grows near trees, the trunks of which it %0a%3c ascends, and hangs down therefrom in numerous tufts of black, %0a%3c rush-like hair, much like a horse’s tail in appearance. The %0a%3c branches, we are told, are thin and articulated, and the leaves, %0a%3c few in number, small, and thin, the seed round, and similar to %0a%3c coriander in appearance, and the root ligneous: it grows, they %0a%3c say, in plantations more particularly. %0a%3c %0a%3c This plant is possessed of astringent properties. The juice %0a%3c of it, kept in the nostrils, arrests bleeding therefrom, and it %0a%3c acts astringently upon the bowels. Taken in doses of three %0a%3c cyathi, in sweet wine, it is a cure for dysentery, is an efficient %0a%3c diuretic, and is curative of cough, hardness of breathing, rup¬ %0a%3c tures, and serpiginous affections. For diseases of the intestines %0a%3c and bladder, the leaves are taken in drink; it has the property, %0a%3c also, of reducing ruptures of the groin. %0a%3c %0a%3c The Greek writers describe another 15 hippuris, also, with %0a%3c shorter tufts, softer and whiter. This last, they say, is remark¬ %0a%3c ably good for sciatica, and, applied with vinegar, for wounds, %0a%3c it having the property of stanching the blood. Bruised nyrn- %0a%3c pluea 16 is also applied to wounds. Peucedanum 17 is taken in drink %0a%3c with cypress seed, for discharges of blood at the mouth or by %0a%3c the lower passages. Sideritis 79 is possessed of such remark¬ %0a%3c able virtues, that applied to the wound of a gladiator just %0a%3c inflicted, it will stop the flow of blood; an effect which is equally %0a%3c produced by an application of charred fennel-giant, or of the %0a%3c %0a%3c 75 Identified by Littre with the Ephedra fragilis of Linnaeus. Feegivs %0a%3c as its synonym the Equisaetum arvense of Linnaeus, the Common horse-tail, %0a%3c or Corn horse-tail. 76 See B. xxv. c. 37. %0a%3c %0a%3c 77 See B. xxv. c. 70. 78 See B. xxv. c. 15. %0a%3c 