s. The following are also %0a%3c good detergents for wounds : heraclion siderion, 2 apollinaris/ %0a%3c psyllion, 4 tragacantha, 6 and scordotis 6 mixed with honey. %0a%3c Powdered scordotis, applied by itself, consumes fleshy excres¬ %0a%3c cences on the body. Polemonia 7 is curative of the malignant %0a%3c ulcer known as “ cacoethes.” The greater centaury, 8 sprinkled %0a%3c in powder, or applied in the form of a liniment, or the leaves of %0a%3c the smaller 9 centaury, boiled or pounded, act as a detergent %0a%3c upon inveterate ulcers, and effect a cure. To recent wounds, %0a%3c the follicules of the clymenus 10 are applied. Gentian is applied %0a%3c to serpiginous ulcers, the root being bruised or else boiled down %0a%3c in water to the consistency of honey ; the juice also of the %0a%3c plant is employed. For wounds, a kind of lycium 11 is prepared %0a%3c from gentian. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 95 See B. xi. c. 39, and B. xx. c. 32 . 96 See B. xxiii. c. 13. %0a%3c %0a%3c 97 See B. xxv. c. 11, et seq. 98 See B. xxv. c. 15. %0a%3c %0a%3c 99 For a description of this substance, see B. xxxiv. c. 24. %0a%3c %0a%3c 1 See B. xviii. c. 14. 2 See B. xxv. c. 15. %0a%3c %0a%3c 3 See B. xxv. c. 17. 4 See B. xxv. c. 90. %0a%3c %0a%3c 8 See B. xiii. c. 36. 6 See B. xxv. c. 27. %0a%3c %0a%3c 7 See B. xxv. c. 28. 8 See B. xxv. c. 30. %0a%3c %0a%3c 9 See B. xxv. c. 31. 10 See B. xxv. c. 33. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 11 See B. xxiv. c. 77. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDIES FOR ULCERS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 207 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 87.] %0a%3c %0a%3c Lysiraachia 12 is curative of recent wounds, and plantago 13 of %0a%3c all kinds of ulcerations,those on females, infants, and aged per¬ %0a%3c sons more particularly. This plant, when softened by the action %0a%3c of fire, is better still: in combination with cerate it acts as a %0a%3c detergent upon ulcers with indurated edges, and arrests the %0a%3c progress of corrosive sores: when applied bruised, it should be %0a%3c covered with its own leaves. Chelidonia 14 also acts as a %0a%3c desiccative upon suppurations, abscesses, and fistulous ulcers ; %0a%3c indeed, it is so remarkably useful for the cure of wounds, as %0a%3c to be employed as a substitute for spodium 15 even. In cases %0a%3c where the cure is almost hopeless, it is applied with axle- %0a%3c grease. Dittany, 16 taken internally, causes arrows to fall from %0a%3c the flesh ; used as a liniment, it has the effect of extracting other %0a%3c kinds of pointed weapons: the leaves are taken in the pro¬ %0a%3c portion of one obolus to one cyathus of water. Nearly equal %0a%3c in its efficacy is pseudo-dictamnon : 17 they are both of them %0a%3c useful, also, for dispersing suppurations. %0a%3c %0a%3c Aristolochia 18 cauterizes putrid sores, and, applied with honey, %0a%3c acts as a detergent upon sordid ulcers. At the same time also, %0a%3c it removes maggots, and extracts hard cores, and all foreign %0a%3c bodies adhering to the flesh, arrows more particularly, and, %0a%3c applied with resin, splintered bones. Used by itself, it fills the %0a%3c cavities made by ulcers with new flesh, and, employed with %0a%3c his, 19 in vinegar, it closes recent wounds. Vervain, or cinque¬ %0a%3c foil with salt and honey, is remedial for ulcers of long stand¬ %0a%3c ing. Roots of persolata 20 are applied to recent wounds in¬ %0a%3c flicted with iron, but for old wounds, it is the leaves that are %0a%3c employed : in both cases, in combination with axle-grease, the %0a%3c sore being then covered with the leaves of the plant. Damaso- %0a%3c niunr 1 is used for wounds the same way as for scrofula, 22 and %0a%3c leaves of verbascum 23 are employed with vinegar or wine. %0a%3c %0a%3c Vervain is useful for all kinds of callosities or putrid sores; %0a%3c root of nymphaea heraclia 24 is curative of running ulcers ; and %0a%3c %0a%3c 12 See B. xxv. c. 35. 13 See B. xxv. c. 39. %0a%3c %0a%3c 14 See B. xxv. c. 50. %0a%3c %0a%3c 15 See B. xix. c. 4, B. xxiii. c. 35, and 